</script>
<script>
const DOCS=[{"id": "doc0", "md": "# Home Laser Resurfacing Research\n\nResearch thread: finding an **at-home device that improves skin quality — pigmentation/PIH, tone/brightness, and long-term collagen/fine lines** — ideally approaching what an in-office **Clear + Brilliant** delivers.\n\n> **Distinct from the parent repo.** The top-level `IPL Device Research` project is about **broadband IPL for hair removal + redness**. This subfolder is a *different device class*: **non-ablative fractional infrared lasers** (Clear + Brilliant, Fraxel, Tria, NIRA, YDUNVIE). Different chromophore (water, not melanin/hemoglobin), different goal (resurfacing/collagen, not hair).\n\n## TL;DR\n\n1. **The category you want is *non-ablative fractional infrared laser*.** Clear + Brilliant is the in-office benchmark. Home members: **Tria FRX, PaloVia, Philips RéAura, MimiSilk Iris, YDUNVIE Iris Ice/Dora.** NIRA, LYMA, JOVS and LED masks are a *gentler adjacent category* — not true resurfacers. See [01](01_laser_resurfacing_science.md).\n2. **Match wavelength to the problem:** **1927nm = pigment/brightness** (superficial — Perméa/Moxi/LaseMD; home = YDUNVIE **Dora**). **1450nm = collagen/texture** (deeper — C+B Original/Fraxel; home = **Tria FRX**, YDUNVIE **Iris Ice**). See [01](01_laser_resurfacing_science.md) §2. **For a 25-yo whose priority is pigment → 1927nm is the evidence-based pick** (1450nm is better-studied but for *acne/collagen*, not pigment); full head-to-head + recommendation in [09](09_1927nm_vs_1450nm_headtohead.md).\n3. **A home device cannot equal Clear + Brilliant — and the quantified reason is NOT energy, depth, or beam diameter.** Per-microbeam energy is genuinely similar (home 5–12 mJ vs C+B 4–9 mJ ✅), **depth is set by wavelength** (all 1440/1450nm devices ≈ equal, ~300–450 µm), and **per-column fluence even favors home** (small ~100 µm spot at 12 mJ ≈ 150 J/cm² > C+B 140 µm/9 mJ ≈ 58 J/cm²). **The gap is coverage density per session + supervised dose control.** C+B treats ~10% coverage / ~650–1,270 MTZ/cm² per session; back-calculating from \"180 J full-face,\" a home Iris/MimiSilk/Tria device delivers only **~30–180 MTZ/cm² (~0.3–1.5% coverage) — roughly 10–30× less density per session.** Full math + cross-checks in [08 §3b](08_clear_brilliant_quantified_gap.md); expectations in [02](02_in_office_vs_at_home.md).\n4. **Most trustworthy home buy = Tria FRX** (✅ FDA K130459, 1450±50nm fractional, real company). **Best pigment-wavelength home option = YDUNVIE Dora (1927nm)** ⚠️ but unverified. **For pigment specifically, topicals + SPF still beat any home laser** (parent [07](../01_ipl_hair_removal/07_alternatives_and_strategy.md)).\n5. **The likely China factory behind the \"Iris\" devices = Jiangsu Unimed / YDUNVIE / 易科美 / Olemy** (✅ FDA K182498; funded company, China's first home 1450nm fractional laser). **Model-code map:** **A9 = Iris Ice** (1450nm flagship, collagen/texture), **A8 = Dora** (1927nm, pigment/brightening), A7 = base Iris. **MimiSilk Iris (~$599) ≈ the 1450nm Iris (A7) by spec-fingerprint** but markets itself as \"Danish\" and sells *no* 1927nm version — so **for the pigment (Dora/1927nm) device you'd need manufacturer-direct.** Full breakdown + purchase paths in [05](05_ydunvie_catalog.md). See also [04](04_suppliers_and_companies.md).\n\n## Documents\n\n| # | File | What it covers |\n|---|------|----------------|\n| 01 | [Laser resurfacing science](01_laser_resurfacing_science.md) | Device taxonomy (ablative/fractional/setting), water-as-chromophore physics, 1450 vs 1927nm, fractional vs warming, efficacy specs, the unit traps, PIH safety |\n| 02 | [In-office vs at-home](02_in_office_vs_at_home.md) | **Clear + Brilliant (✅ verified specs) vs home devices — what's different, what to realistically expect** for pigment + collagen |\n| 03 | [Device landscape](03_device_landscape.md) | **Every comparable home/discontinued device ranked** (Tria, PaloVia, RéAura, MimiSilk, YDUNVIE Iris/Dora, OYAY, NIRA, Iluminage, LYMA, JOVS, DermRays) + clinical relatives |\n| 04 | [Suppliers & companies](04_suppliers_and_companies.md) | **Jiangsu Unimed/YDUNVIE deep profile + China supply chain + FDA 510(k) supplier map** + where they sell, China pricing, Alibaba matching, screening + red flags |\n| 05 | [YDUNVIE catalog](05_ydunvie_catalog.md) | **All ~31 YDUNVIE products** analyzed line-by-line (Iris, Dora, Velar, Nova, etc.) |\n| 06 | [Sourcing & RFQ templates](06_sourcing_rfq_templates.md) | Copy-paste RFQs (1450nm / 1927nm / 1064nm / VCSEL), universal spec sheet, screening, standards |\n| 07 | [Future research plan](07_future_research_plan.md) | **Phased plan** to verify specs, map the market, review clinical efficacy, source & decide |\n| 08 | [The quantified gap](08_clear_brilliant_quantified_gap.md) | **Dermatology evidence: exactly how Clear + Brilliant differs from home devices.** Energy ≈ similar, depth ≈ wavelength-set, beam diameter/fluence ≈ matched (even favors home) — **the gap is density/coverage + dose control**, quantified with numbers |\n| 09 | [1927nm vs 1450nm head-to-head](09_1927nm_vs_1450nm_headtohead.md) | **Wavelength decision for a 25-yo, pigment-focused user.** The evidence comparison + recommendation: 1450nm is better-studied *for acne/collagen*, but **1927nm is the evidence-based pigment wavelength** |\n| 10 | [Where to buy — storefronts](10_where_to_buy_storefronts.md) | **Every storefront selling each device**, with all YDUNVIE models (A7/A9/Dora) by channel + price, dropship tells, and how to buy without getting burned |\n| 11 | [Subscriber Q&A — low-density rejuvenation](11_subscriber_qa_lowdensity_rejuvenation.md) | A reader's \"month-of-home ≈ one C+B?\" question + **how a laser-specialty derm would answer and why** (coverage ≠ remodeling); includes a short drafted reply |\n| 12 | [Alibaba supplier scan (live)](12_alibaba_supplier_scan.md) | **Live Alibaba browse:** no consumer handheld exists there; YDUNVIE/Focuslight absent; 6 md04 clinic-machine suppliers confirmed + OEM laser-module sources (incl. a 1440nm diode chip) |\n| 13 | [Tria SmoothBeauty owner's guide](13_tria_smoothbeauty_owners_guide.md) | **The device in hand, ID'd + spec'd from its primary-source manuals** (PDFs mirrored in `tria_smoothbeauty/`). SmoothBeauty = Age-Defying = FRX (model SRL, ✅ FDA 2013). ✅ verified specs (1440nm, 5–12 mJ, Class 1), coverage/density estimate, indication-vs-marketing reality, and a full **quick-start + 12-week protocol** |\n\n## Confidence legend\n✅ **Verified** (FDA 510(k) / peer-reviewed / official spec) · ⚠️ **Marketing claim** (seller/brand, unconfirmed) · 🔍 **Inferred** (from wavelength/category)\n\n> **Provenance & honesty note.** This folder organizes a prior research conversation (much of it from brand/marketing pages, which are error-prone). The **anchor facts were re-verified** against FDA filings and clinical sources during this pass (Clear+Brilliant, NIRA, Tria, PaloVia, RéAura, Jiangsu Unimed K182498). Everything still marked ⚠️/🔍 needs primary-source confirmation — that's exactly what [07](07_future_research_plan.md) is for. Treat ⚠️ specs (esp. YDUNVIE/OYAY/MimiSilk numbers) as *claims to verify*, not facts.\n\n## Status / open items\n- **Verified this pass:** Clear+Brilliant Touch (1440/1927nm specs), NIRA (K163137/K222685), Tria FAN (K130459), PaloVia (K090525), RéAura (1435nm+Solta), Jiangsu Unimed (K182498 valid).\n- **Tria specs upgraded ⚠️→✅ from primary-source IFU** ([13](13_tria_smoothbeauty_owners_guide.md)): SmoothBeauty/Age-Defying/FRX are one device (model SRL) — 1440nm diode, **5–12 mJ/pulse**, Class 1, indication = periorbital wrinkles only (IFU explicitly **not** for pigment/dyschromia/freckles/veins). Manuals mirrored at `tria_smoothbeauty/source_docs/`.\n- **Partially resolved:** MimiSilk Iris ≈ YDUNVIE Iris (A7) by spec-fingerprint (1450nm, 12 mJ, 100 µm microbeam), but MimiSilk doesn't disclose the YDUNVIE/Jiangsu Unimed link (claims \"Danish\") and sells only the 1450nm model. Model codes mapped: A9=Iris Ice, A8=Dora(1927nm), A7=Iris. See [05](05_ydunvie_catalog.md).\n- **Open (high-value):** Confirm **Dora is truly 1927nm** (retail copy conflicts with 1450nm) — *the* spec for the pigment goal. Does Iris Ice **Plus**/A9 out-perform base Iris or just add UX/cert? Real clinical efficacy of home NAF vs Clear+Brilliant? Buyable 1927nm home device with credible PIH-safety data? → [07](07_future_research_plan.md).\n- **Not yet done:** primary 510(k) PDFs not yet mirrored into the repo (planned in Phase 1).\n", "file": "README.md"}, {"id": "doc1", "md": "# Science Brief: Non-Ablative Fractional Laser Resurfacing (Pigment + Collagen)\n\n**Goal of this thread:** find an *at-home* device that meaningfully improves **skin quality** — pigmentation/PIH, tone/brightness, and long-term collagen/fine lines — ideally approaching what an in-office **Clear + Brilliant** does.\n\n> **How this differs from the parent repo.** The main `IPL Device Research` project is about **broadband IPL for hair removal + redness**. This subfolder is a *different device class*: **fractional / non-ablative infrared lasers** (Clear + Brilliant, Fraxel, Tria, NIRA, etc.). Different physics, different chromophore, different goal. Read the parent repo's [07_alternatives_and_strategy](../01_ipl_hair_removal/07_alternatives_and_strategy.md) first — its core finding (for pigment-prone skin, lead with topicals + photoprotection, not energy devices) still governs everything here.\n\n**Confidence legend used throughout this folder:**\n- ✅ **Verified** — FDA 510(k) filing, peer-reviewed clinical paper, or official manufacturer spec sheet\n- ⚠️ **Marketing claim** — from a seller/brand/retail page, not independently confirmed\n- 🔍 **Inferred** — reasoned from wavelength/category physics; needs primary-source confirmation\n\n---\n\n## 1. The device taxonomy — where each thing sits\n\nThere are three axes that matter. Almost every confusion in the marketing comes from collapsing them.\n\n| Axis | Option A | Option B | Why it matters |\n|------|----------|----------|----------------|\n| **Ablation** | **Ablative** (CO₂ 10,600nm, Er:YAG 2940nm) — vaporizes tissue | **Non-ablative** (1410–1927nm) — heats but leaves surface intact | Ablative = dramatic results + real downtime + high PIH risk. **All home pigment/collagen devices are non-ablative.** |\n| **Fractionation** | **Fractional** — treats microscopic columns, leaves bridges of intact skin between | **Non-fractional / bulk** — heats a whole zone uniformly | Fractional = faster healing, controlled injury, the basis of Fraxel/Clear+Brilliant/Tria. Non-fractional (NIRA) = gentler dermal warming, no true resurfacing. |\n| **Setting/power** | **In-office** (Clear+Brilliant, Fraxel, Moxi) — provider-controlled, high energy | **At-home / OTC** (Tria, NIRA, YDUNVIE) — capped energy for safety | The energy gap is the whole story (see [02_in_office_vs_at_home](02_in_office_vs_at_home.md)). |\n\n**The category you actually want for skin quality:** *non-ablative **fractional** infrared laser*. Clear + Brilliant is the in-office reference. Tria FRX, PaloVia, Philips RéAura, MimiSilk Iris, and YDUNVIE Iris Ice are the home members. NIRA is the odd one out — it is non-ablative but **non-fractional**, so it is a \"dermal warmer,\" not a resurfacer.\n\n---\n\n## 2. The governing physics: water as the chromophore\n\nIPL targets **melanin and hemoglobin** (pigment, hair, vessels). These resurfacing lasers target **water**, which is everywhere in skin. By heating water in tiny columns, you create **microthermal zones (MTZs)** — controlled micro-injuries that trigger a wound-healing/remodeling cascade: epidermal turnover (pushes out pigment) + dermal collagen stimulation (fine lines, texture).\n\n**Water absorption rises with wavelength in this band**, and that single fact determines depth and target:\n\n| Wavelength | Water absorption | Penetration depth (approx) | Best target | ✅/source |\n|-----------|------------------|---------------------------|-------------|-----------|\n| **1410–1450nm** | moderate | **deeper (~280–400 µm)** | dermal collagen, texture, pores, fine lines, shallow acne marks | ✅ depths from a 1440/1927 NAF diode study: 1440nm reaches ~280/340/390 µm by energy level |\n| **1470nm** | moderate | deep | collagen/texture (OEM/clinic) | 🔍 |\n| **1550nm** | higher | deep (Fraxel re:store class) | dermal remodeling, scars, deeper wrinkles | ✅ Fraxel re:store |\n| **1927nm** | **high** | **shallow (~170 µm)** | **superficial pigment, dullness, melasma/PIH-prone discoloration, brightening** | ✅ 1927nm handpiece reaches ~170 µm at 5 mJ |\n\n**The single most important takeaway for pigment vs collagen:**\n- **Pigmentation / PIH / brown spots / dullness / brightening → 1927nm** (superficial, where epidermal pigment lives). This is Clear + Brilliant **Perméa**, Sciton **Moxi**, **LaseMD**, and the home YDUNVIE **Dora**.\n- **Collagen / texture / pores / fine lines → 1440–1550nm** (deeper, into the dermis). This is Clear + Brilliant **Original**, **Fraxel**, **Tria FRX**, **NIRA**, and the home YDUNVIE **Iris Ice**.\n\n> \"Deeper\" ≠ \"better.\" For pigment, the *superficial* 1927nm is the right tool because the target is in the epidermis. Pushing a deeper 1450nm beam past the pigment just adds dermal heat — which in pigment-prone skin can *worsen* PIH. Match the wavelength to the depth of the problem.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Mechanism difference: fractional injury vs bulk warming\n\nThis is why NIRA is not a Clear + Brilliant substitute even though the wavelengths are close.\n\n- **Fractional (Clear+Brilliant, Tria FRX, YDUNVIE Iris/Dora):** create discrete columns of controlled thermal injury, leaving untreated skin between them. The injury drives epidermal turnover (pigment) and dermal remodeling (collagen). This is what produces *resurfacing*-type results — texture, pores, tone, mild pigment.\n- **Non-fractional warming (NIRA):** ✅ NIRA's own framing is heating the dermis above ~39°C to activate heat-shock-protein / collagen pathways while staying below the pain threshold. No micro-injury columns, so no true resurfacing. It is a **daily/low-downtime collagen-maintenance** tool, not a pigment or resurfacing device.\n\nSo the mechanistic ranking for *visible remodeling*:\n**In-office fractional (Clear+Brilliant/Fraxel) > home fractional (Tria/YDUNVIE) > home non-fractional warming (NIRA).**\nBut the *downtime/convenience* ranking is the exact inverse.\n\n---\n\n## 4. What makes a treatment \"efficacious\" — the spec ceiling\n\nMarketing loves to quote one big number. For fractional lasers, **no single number tells you efficacy** — you need the whole set:\n\n| Spec | What it controls | Why a single number misleads |\n|------|------------------|------------------------------|\n| **Energy per microbeam (mJ/pulse)** | depth + intensity of each column | \"12 mJ\" sounds strong but is meaningless without spot size |\n| **Microbeam/spot diameter (µm)** | fluence (energy ÷ area) | a wide low-mJ beam ≠ a tight high-mJ beam |\n| **Density (MTZs/cm² or % coverage)** | how much skin is treated per pass | low density = gentle but slow/weak results |\n| **Total delivered energy (J, full-face)** | cumulative dose | a \"180 J full-face\" headline mixes units with per-pulse mJ |\n| **Treatment depth (µm)** | which target you reach | epidermal (pigment) vs dermal (collagen) |\n| **Number of sessions** | cumulative remodeling | one session of anything does little |\n| **Wavelength + tolerance (nm ± nm)** | the target itself | 1450 vs 1927 is the whole pigment-vs-collagen split |\n\n**Unit trap to watch (appears constantly in YDUNVIE/OYAY listings):** *\"180 J full-face\"* (total accumulated energy over a whole treatment) is **not** comparable to *\"12 mJ/pulse\"* (energy in one microbeam). A device can have identical 12 mJ/pulse but very different full-face totals depending on density, time, and area. **Always force sellers onto the same units before comparing** (see [06_sourcing_rfq_templates](06_sourcing_rfq_templates.md)).\n\n---\n\n## 5. The home-vs-clinical energy gap (the honest reality)\n\n✅ Verified spec anchors (full detail and citations in [02_in_office_vs_at_home](02_in_office_vs_at_home.md) and [03_device_landscape](03_device_landscape.md)):\n\n| Device | Class | Wavelength | Per-pulse / fluence ceiling |\n|--------|-------|-----------|------------------------------|\n| Clear + Brilliant Original | in-office fractional | 1440nm | **9 mJ** max, 2.5 W avg |\n| Clear + Brilliant Perméa | in-office fractional | 1927nm | **5 mJ** max, 0.9 W avg |\n| Tria FRX (FAN) | home fractional | 1450±50nm | ~5–12 mJ/pulse ⚠️ (marketing) |\n| PaloVia | home fractional | 1410nm | ~10–15 mJ ⚠️ |\n| NIRA Model 2 | home **non-fractional** | 1450nm | 2.1–3.8 J/cm² (fluence), 2 W |\n| YDUNVIE Iris Ice / Plus | home fractional | 1450nm | 3–12 mJ/pulse ⚠️ (OEM/seller) |\n\nInterestingly, the **per-microbeam energy of home fractional devices (5–12 mJ) overlaps Clear + Brilliant's own 5–9 mJ** — and at a matched wavelength so does the **depth** (depth is set by wavelength, not by the device). The clinical gap is **not** mainly energy or depth — it's **density/coverage, scan precision, dual-wavelength capability, number of passes, and a provider tuning aggression to a clinical endpoint**. A home device fires **fewer, less-dense, more conservative** columns (at the same depth) and caps aggression for safety. That's why it takes far more home sessions for a fraction of the result — but it is not *nothing*, especially cumulatively. (Quantified in [08](08_clear_brilliant_quantified_gap.md).)\n\n---\n\n## 6. PIH / safety — the constraint that dominates pigment-prone skin\n\nThe reason this whole thread needs caution: **any thermal/injury device can trigger post-inflammatory hyperpigmentation (PIH) in melanin-rich or pigment-prone skin.** A device sold \"for brightening\" can *worsen* brown discoloration if energy, density, cooling, or instructions are poor.\n\nProtective factors to demand in any device:\n- **Cooling** (contact/sapphire/\"ice\") to protect the epidermis\n- **Lower density / conservative energy** options\n- **Skin-tone guidance / sensor** and explicit Fitzpatrick limits\n- **Eye-safety design** (mandatory for any home laser near the periorbital area)\n- A protocol that spaces sessions and ramps slowly\n\n**Contraindications that recur across these devices:** pregnancy, active acne/infection, melasma (relative — can flare), isotretinoin use, photosensitizing meds, recent sun exposure/tan. Always pair with strict daily SPF — without photoprotection, any pigment gains reverse.\n\n---\n\n## 7. One-paragraph synthesis\n\nFor **pigment/PIH/brightness**, the right physics is **1927nm fractional** (Perméa / Moxi / LaseMD in-office; YDUNVIE **Dora** at home). For **collagen/texture/pores/fine lines**, it's **1440–1550nm fractional** (Clear+Brilliant Original / Fraxel in-office; **Tria FRX**, **YDUNVIE Iris Ice** at home). **NIRA** is a gentle non-fractional dermal warmer — good low-downtime collagen maintenance, weak for pigment. No home device closes the clinical gap, but home **fractional** devices (Tria / YDUNVIE / PaloVia) are genuinely the *same category* as Clear + Brilliant, whereas non-fractional and LED/VCSEL devices are a softer adjacent category. Whatever the device, **cooling + conservative settings + daily SPF** are non-negotiable for pigment-prone skin.\n\n---\n\n### Sources (this brief)\n- [Clear + Brilliant Touch clinical protocol (NCT05027282)](https://clinicaltrials.gov/study/NCT05027282) — 1440/1927nm combination\n- [The 1440nm and 1927nm Nonablative Fractional Diode Laser — JDD review](https://jddonline.com/articles/article-the-1440-nm-and-1927-nm-nonablative-fractional-diode-laser-current-trends-and-future-directi-S1545961620S00s3X/) — depths, targets\n- [NIRA Model 2 510(k) K222685](https://www.accessdata.fda.gov/cdrh_docs/pdf22/K222685.pdf) — 1450nm non-fractional, fluence, 39°C/HSP mechanism framing\n- [Tria FAN System 510(k) K130459](https://www.accessdata.fda.gov/cdrh_docs/pdf13/k130459.pdf) — 1450±50nm fractional, periorbital\n- [PaloVia home NAF laser multicenter trial (ScienceDirect)](https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0190962212001430) — 1410nm, internal scanner\n", "file": "01_laser_resurfacing_science.md"}, {"id": "doc2", "md": "# In-Office Clear + Brilliant vs At-Home Lasers: What's Different, What to Expect\n\n**The honest answer up front:** A home device cannot reproduce a Clear + Brilliant treatment. It *can* deliver a milder, slower, cumulative version of the same **mechanism** — if you pick a true **fractional** device and commit to a long, consistent schedule. The gap is real but it is one of **degree and speed**, not category — provided you compare a home *fractional* laser to Clear + Brilliant, not a non-fractional warmer or an LED mask.\n\n---\n\n## 1. What Clear + Brilliant actually is (✅ verified specs)\n\nClear + Brilliant is Solta Medical's entry-level, in-office, **non-ablative fractional diode laser** — often marketed as \"baby Fraxel.\" The current **Touch** platform has two interchangeable handpieces:\n\n| Handpiece | Wavelength ✅ | Max avg power ✅ | Max pulse energy ✅ | Pulse width ✅ | Primary job |\n|-----------|--------------|------------------|---------------------|----------------|-------------|\n| **Original** | 1440 ± 20 nm | 2.5 W | **9 mJ** | 3 ms | texture, pores, fine lines, mild resurfacing, collagen |\n| **Perméa** | 1927 ± 20 nm | 0.9 W | **5 mJ** | 5 ms | superficial pigment, dullness, brightening, melasma/PIH-prone tone |\n\nClassified Class 1C laser (IEC 60825-1). Depth: 1440nm reaches roughly **0.3–0.4 mm**; 1927nm Perméa is much more superficial at **~0.17 mm**. ([Source: NCT05027282 protocol](https://clinicaltrials.gov/study/NCT05027282); JDD 1440/1927 NAF diode review.)\n\n**What a course looks like (typical clinical protocol):**\n- A series of **4–6 sessions**, spaced ~2–4 weeks apart, then maintenance every few months.\n- ~20–30 min per session (numbing cream first).\n- **Downtime:** \"sandpaper\"/grainy texture + redness for 2–5 days; pigment \"MENDS\" (microscopic epidermal necrotic debris) slough over a week with Perméa.\n- **Cost:** typically **$300–$600 per session** in the US (varies by market) → a course is roughly **$1,500–$3,000+**.\n- **Results:** smoother texture, smaller-looking pores, brighter/more even tone, gradual fine-line softening; collagen remodeling builds over months. Provider tunes density/energy per pass and per skin response.\n\n---\n\n## 2. What at-home fractional lasers are (the honest version)\n\nThe closest home analogs (Tria FRX, PaloVia, YDUNVIE Iris Ice/Dora, MimiSilk Iris) use the **same wavelengths and the same fractional mechanism**, but with the aggression dialed down for unsupervised consumer safety.\n\n| Dimension | In-office Clear + Brilliant | At-home fractional laser | The real gap |\n|-----------|----------------------------|--------------------------|--------------|\n| **Wavelength** | 1440nm + 1927nm (both available) | usually *one* (1450nm **or** 1927nm) | Home = single target per device; C+B switches handpieces |\n| **Per-microbeam energy** | 5–9 mJ ✅ | 3–12 mJ ⚠️ (overlaps!) | **Smaller gap than you'd think** |\n| **Density / coverage** | high, provider-set | low, fixed/capped | **This is where most of the gap lives** |\n| **Depth** | wavelength-set (~300–400µm @1440nm) | **same at matched wavelength** | **not a gap at same λ** — depth follows wavelength, not the device |\n| **Scan precision** | optical scanner, uniform | handheld glide/stamp, user-dependent | uneven coverage at home |\n| **Sessions to result** | 4–6 + maintenance | dozens, over months–years | home = much slower |\n| **Downtime** | 2–5 days redness/flaking | minimal (minutes of warmth/pinkness) | home wins on convenience |\n| **Cost** | $1,500–$3,000+ /course | $500–$1,000 one-time device ⚠️ | home wins on $ if it works |\n| **Supervision** | dermatologist/provider | you, alone | safety + tuning lost at home |\n\n**Key insight:** the per-pulse *energy* of home fractional devices actually overlaps Clear + Brilliant's, and at matched wavelength so does the *depth*. The clinical superiority comes from **density/coverage, dual-wavelength capability, scan uniformity, and a provider escalating aggression to an endpoint** — not from energy or depth. A home device fires **fewer, less-dense, more conservative** columns (at the same depth). So you get a *real but fractional fraction* of the effect, requiring far more sessions. (Quantified in [08 §3b](08_clear_brilliant_quantified_gap.md).)\n\n---\n\n## 3. What to realistically expect\n\n### From in-office Clear + Brilliant\n- **Pigment/tone (Perméa 1927nm):** visible brightening and more even tone over a course; good for dullness, superficial sun spots, some melasma (with caution). Among the safer in-office options for pigment-prone skin *because* it's superficial + provider-controlled.\n- **Collagen/texture (Original 1440nm):** smoother skin, refined pores, gradual fine-line softening; collagen builds over 3–6 months.\n- **Timeline:** glow within days of each session; structural change over the full course + maintenance.\n\n### From an at-home fractional laser (Tria FRX / YDUNVIE Iris Ice / Dora / PaloVia)\n- **Realistic wins:** gradual improvement in texture, smoothness, \"glow,\" minor tone evening, slow fine-line softening — *if used consistently for months and the device is genuinely fractional at a real wavelength.*\n- **Realistic limits:** will not match a C+B course's per-session density or speed; will not clear significant pigment, melasma, or scars on its own; results plateau lower.\n- **Best framing:** a **maintenance / between-treatments / budget-substitute** tool, not a clinical replacement. Pairs well *after* an in-office course to extend results.\n\n### From at-home **non-fractional** (NIRA) or LED/VCSEL (LYMA, masks)\n- **NIRA:** gentle dermal warming → modest collagen/fine-line maintenance, especially periorbital, with near-zero downtime and daily-use cadence. **Weak for pigment.** Not a resurfacer.\n- **LED/VCSEL/LLLT (LYMA, JOVS, masks):** lowest risk, lowest intensity; better for redness/inflammation/general skin quality and maintenance than for pigment correction or resurfacing.\n\n---\n\n## 4. The decision framing for *your* goals (pigment + long-term collagen)\n\n| Your priority | Best in-office | Best at-home analog | Notes |\n|---------------|----------------|---------------------|-------|\n| **Pigment / PIH / brightness / tone** | Clear + Brilliant **Perméa 1927nm** (or Moxi/LaseMD) | **YDUNVIE Dora (1927nm)** ⚠️ | superficial 1927nm is the right physics; home version needs spec verification |\n| **Collagen / texture / pores / fine lines** | Clear + Brilliant **Original 1440nm** (or Fraxel) | **Tria FRX (1450nm)** ✅-cleared, or **YDUNVIE Iris Ice (1450nm)** ⚠️ | true fractional, deeper |\n| **Lowest-risk maintenance, near-zero downtime** | (n/a) | **NIRA** ✅-cleared | non-fractional; gentle; weak for pigment |\n| **The \"do it right\" path** | A short C+B course (esp. Perméa for pigment) | + home fractional for maintenance | best results come from in-office *led*, home *maintained* |\n\n> **Strong recommendation that survives all the marketing:** for **pigment specifically**, the highest-confidence, lowest-PIH-risk plan is **not** \"buy a stronger home laser.\" It is the parent repo's conclusion — **iron-oxide tinted SPF + topicals (azelaic acid, tranexamic acid, niacinamide, retinoid) ~70–80% of the effort**, with energy devices as the minority adjunct. A home fractional laser is a reasonable *collagen/texture* tool and a *modest* pigment helper; it is not a substitute for photoprotection + actives on pigment. See [../07_alternatives_and_strategy.md](../01_ipl_hair_removal/07_alternatives_and_strategy.md).\n\n---\n\n## 5. Bottom line\n\n- **Can a home device equal Clear + Brilliant?** No — not in per-session density, dual-wavelength range, or speed. (Depth is *not* the gap — at matched wavelength it's the same.)\n- **Can a home *fractional* device deliver the same *mechanism* at a milder dose?** Yes — Tria FRX, PaloVia, and the YDUNVIE Iris/Dora family are genuinely the same category, just dialed down. Expect a slow, cumulative fraction of the result.\n- **Is a home *non-fractional* (NIRA) or LED device \"like\" Clear + Brilliant?** No — different, gentler category. Fine for maintenance, weak for pigment/resurfacing.\n- **For your pigment goal:** the right *wavelength* is 1927nm (home: Dora; clinic: Perméa/Moxi/LaseMD), but the right *primary strategy* is still topicals + SPF, with the laser as adjunct.\n- **For your collagen goal:** a home 1450nm fractional device (Tria FRX is the only FDA-cleared, verifiable one) used consistently for months is a legitimate maintenance tool.\n\nSee [03_device_landscape](03_device_landscape.md) for every comparable device ranked, and [04_suppliers_and_companies](04_suppliers_and_companies.md) for who makes them.\n\n---\n\n### Sources\n- [Clear + Brilliant Touch protocol — NCT05027282](https://clinicaltrials.gov/study/NCT05027282) (1440/1927nm specs, depths)\n- [JDD: 1440nm & 1927nm Nonablative Fractional Diode Laser review](https://jddonline.com/articles/article-the-1440-nm-and-1927-nm-nonablative-fractional-diode-laser-current-trends-and-future-directi-S1545961620S00s3X/)\n- [NIRA Model 2 510(k) K222685](https://www.accessdata.fda.gov/cdrh_docs/pdf22/K222685.pdf)\n- [Tria FAN System 510(k) K130459](https://www.accessdata.fda.gov/cdrh_docs/pdf13/k130459.pdf)\n", "file": "02_in_office_vs_at_home.md"}, {"id": "doc3", "md": "# Device Landscape: Every Home / Discontinued Laser Comparable to Clear + Brilliant\n\nRanked by **how close they are to an efficacious (in-office, fractional) treatment** for skin quality. Confidence: ✅ verified / ⚠️ marketing claim / 🔍 inferred.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Master comparison table\n\n| Device | Region / status | Wavelength | Fractional? | Energy ceiling | Best target | Closeness to C+B |\n|--------|-----------------|-----------|-------------|----------------|-------------|------------------|\n| **Clear + Brilliant Original** *(reference)* | in-office | 1440nm ✅ | Yes | 9 mJ / 2.5 W ✅ | texture, pores, collagen | — (benchmark) |\n| **Clear + Brilliant Perméa** *(reference)* | in-office | 1927nm ✅ | Yes | 5 mJ / 0.9 W ✅ | superficial pigment, brightening | — (benchmark) |\n| **Tria FRX (Age-Defying / FAN)** | US, **on sale** | 1450±50nm ✅ | Yes ✅ | 5–12 mJ/pulse ⚠️ | periorbital wrinkles, texture, mild tone | ★★★★ closest *buyable, FDA-cleared* |\n| **PaloVia Skin Renewing Laser** | US, **discontinued** | 1410nm ✅ | Yes ✅ (internal scanner) | ~10–15 mJ ⚠️ | periorbital wrinkles | ★★★★ closest *historical* |\n| **Philips RéAura SC5000** | EU/UK, **discontinued** | 1435nm ✅ | Yes ✅ (Fraxel-derived, w/ Solta) | n/a | tone, texture, fine lines | ★★★★ most \"Fraxel-at-home\" ever sold |\n| **YDUNVIE Iris Ice / Iris Ice Plus** | China brand, ships intl | 1450nm ⚠️ | Yes ⚠️ | 3–12 mJ/pulse ⚠️ | pores, texture, acne marks, fine lines | ★★★½ strong on paper, verify |\n| **MimiSilk Iris** | online brand (likely YDUNVIE-family) | 1450nm ⚠️ | Yes ⚠️ | ≤12 mJ, ~2.11 J/cm² ⚠️ | collagen, pores, acne marks | ★★★½ likely relabel; verify |\n| **YDUNVIE Dora / Dora Plus / Pro** | China brand | 1927nm ⚠️ | Yes ⚠️ | 2–7 mJ/pulse ⚠️ | **pigment, dullness, brightening** | ★★★½ home \"Perméa/Moxi\" analog |\n| **OYAY Iris Ice Plus / Dora** | dropship storefront | 1450 / 1927nm ⚠️ | Yes ⚠️ | 3–12 / 2–7 mJ ⚠️ | (rebrands of above) | ★★★ same hardware, bad channel |\n| **NIRA Pro / Precision / Model 2** | US, **on sale** | 1450nm ✅ | **No (non-fractional)** ✅ | 2.1–3.8 J/cm² ✅ | fine lines, collagen maintenance | ★★ gentle warmer, not resurfacer |\n| **Iluminage Skin Smoothing Laser** | US, **buyable via reseller (~$598)** | 1440nm ✅ | FDA: not clearly fractional ✅ / listing claims fractional ⚠️ | FDA: 3–4 J/cm², 7mm spot ✅ / listing: 380–500 mJ, 36 spots/s ⚠️ | fine lines, pores, acne scars, tone, spots | ★★–★★★ (hinges on fractional truth) |\n| **Focuslight 1470nm home concept** | China OEM module | 1470nm ✅ | Yes ✅ | 6–12 mJ/spot, 1.5 W ✅ | collagen/texture (OEM platform) | ★★★ tech, not a finished product |\n| **LYMA Laser / PRO** | UK, **on sale** | 808nm + 620nm ✅ | No (LLLT/PBM) ✅ | 62.5 mW/cm² ✅ | low-level photobiomodulation | ★ different category (not resurfacing) |\n| **JOVS 4D / mask (Qianyu)** | China, on sale | 660 + 850nm VCSEL ✅ | No (PBM mask) ✅ | 40–100 mW/cm² ✅ | wrinkle/PBM | ★ different category |\n| **DermRays Revive (Lotuxs)** | China, on sale | 1064nm ✅ | No ✅ | 5–10 J/cm², Rx ✅ | wrinkle/hair removal | ★ different wavelength & class |\n\n---\n\n## 2. The home **fractional** devices (the real comparables)\n\n### Tria FRX — the only buyable, FDA-cleared, verifiable home fractional laser ★★★★\n- ✅ **FDA:** Tria FAN System (K130459) + FANp (K141868). Semiconductor diode, **1450 ± 50 nm**, fractional non-ablative, cleared for **periorbital wrinkles**. Predicates include Palomar LOI, Cynosure Iluminage, Affirm, Solta Fraxel re:fine.\n- ⚠️ Marketing: ~5–12 mJ/pulse; ~$650–$700 retail; \"12 weeks on + 4 weeks off\" cadence; glide handpiece; moderate-to-high pain, some redness/peeling.\n- **Verdict:** the strongest *trustworthy* home option for the **collagen/texture** goal. Conservative on pigment (its own labeling cautions dyschromia/freckles may not respond). The one to buy if you want FDA paperwork + a real company behind it.\n\n### PaloVia Skin Renewing Laser (Palomar LOI) — closest historical match ★★★★\n- ✅ **FDA:** Palomar LOI System K090525, OTC, periorbital wrinkles. **1410 ± 5 nm**, handheld fractional with an **internal scanner** stepping a microbeam through an array. Pivotal trial: ~90% had some periocular wrinkle improvement.\n- **Status:** discontinued. This is the *root predicate* for much of the category (NIRA and Tria both cite Palomar lineage).\n- **Verdict:** historically the purest \"home Fraxel.\" Study target, not a buy.\n\n### Philips RéAura SC5000 — the \"Fraxel-at-home\" ★★★★\n- ✅ **1435nm diode, fractionated non-ablative, co-developed with Solta (Fraxel maker).** Marketed as creating thousands of microscopic beams to renew skin and push out pigmented cells.\n- **Status:** discontinued (EU/UK). Possibly the most explicitly Fraxel-derived consumer device ever sold.\n- **Verdict:** the other big \"forgotten\" device worth studying alongside PaloVia.\n\n### YDUNVIE Iris Ice / Iris Ice Plus — strongest *current* China-market fractional ★★★½\n- ⚠️ Seller specs: **1450nm**, \"nano-matrix\" fractional, contact/\"ice\" cooling, 3–12 mJ/pulse (Plus), 180 J full-face, DynamicScan, depth modes ~300/350/400 µm, ~10 min full-face, 3 treatments/charge.\n- **Iris Ice Plus vs Iris Ice:** *probably not meaningfully stronger* — both top out around **12 mJ/pulse**. \"Plus\" appears to add cooling, sensors, app/zones, shell/UX, and certification marketing rather than raw output. Don't pay a big premium without a same-units spec comparison.\n- ✅ Likely manufacturer: **Jiangsu Unimed Laser** (FDA K182498). See [04_suppliers_and_companies](04_suppliers_and_companies.md).\n- **Verdict:** the most credible China fractional option for **texture/pores/acne marks/collagen** — *if* specs and authorization are verified. Buy through an authorized agent, not a dropship store.\n\n### MimiSilk Iris — likely a YDUNVIE-family relabel ★★★½\n- ⚠️ Sells \"1450nm advanced at-home fractional laser,\" ~$599, ~100 µm microbeam, ≤12 mJ, ~2.11 J/cm² max density. Reddit + reseller trails (myernk = \"authorized YDUNVIE agent\") suggest MimiSilk is the **same Jiangsu Unimed/YDUNVIE hardware** under a Western brand.\n- ✅/⚠️ **FDA clearance now near-confirmed via name match:** MimiSilk's product is titled *\"1450nm **Advanced Skin Renewing Device**,\"* which is the **verbatim device name of Jiangsu Unimed's 510(k) K182498** (cleared Nov 30 2018, product code ONG, microbeam/fractional). So MimiSilk *is* FDA-cleared — but on the **manufacturer's** filing, not a brand-held one (still worth confirming the exact UDI/label on the unit you'd buy).\n- **Verdict:** plausibly identical hardware to Iris Ice with English-market support; verify the regulatory claim and the factory link before trusting.\n\n### YDUNVIE Dora / Dora Plus / Dora Pro — the home **1927nm pigment** option ★★★½\n- ⚠️ Seller specs: **1927nm** non-ablative fractional, 2–7 mJ/pulse, dark spots/renewal/brightening. A related \"A8 / 大白\" listing describes 1927nm fractional for epidermal renewal + melanin metabolism, 3 gears, 2–3×/week, 20–25 min/session (page copy is internally inconsistent — verify).\n- **Verdict:** the most on-target *wavelength* for **your pigment goal** in the home market — a home analog of Perméa/Moxi/LaseMD. But 1927nm pigment devices can also *worsen* PIH if poorly dosed; verify energy/density/cooling and ramp carefully.\n\n### Focuslight 1470nm home module — OEM *component*, not a product ★★★\n- ✅ Focuslight (Xi'an; **public, SSE STAR 688167**, 900+ staff, 400+ patents) supplies a **1470nm** home skin-rejuvenation **module**: 1.5 W, 100×100 µm spot, **6–12 mJ/spot**, single/multi/dot-matrix output; they explicitly benchmark RéAura and Tria and note home NAF spot energy is generally ≤~15 mJ/spot.\n- **Verdict:** a **B2B laser-engine supplier**, not a consumer brand — they sell the module a device maker builds around. Relevant only if you want to **commission/OEM your own device**; for a single unit, buy YDUNVIE/MimiSilk instead. Full company profile in [04 §2a](04_suppliers_and_companies.md).\n\n---\n\n## 3. The adjacent (gentler) categories — often mis-marketed as equivalent\n\n### NIRA (Model 2 / Precision / Pro) — non-fractional warmer ★★\n- ✅ **FDA:** K163137 (Model 1), K222685 (Model 2). **1450 ± 20 nm, non-fractional, non-ablative.** Model 2: 2 W, spot 12.5×13.8 mm², fluence **2.1–3.8 J/cm²**, fan cooling. Owner: **Dermal Photonics Corp** (US). ✅ 76-subject blinded study showed periorbital wrinkle improvement.\n- **Verdict:** legit, low-downtime **collagen maintenance** (esp. under-eye). **Not** a resurfacer, **weak for pigment**. Don't expect Clear + Brilliant results.\n\n### Iluminage Skin Smoothing Laser — same wavelength; fractional status disputed ★★–★★★\n- ✅ **FDA:** K133473 (Cynosure). **1440nm, 3–4 J/cm², 7mm spot**, periorbital/perioral wrinkles. FDA description = energy over a fixed area, **not clearly fractional**.\n- ⚠️ **Retail listing** ([myernk, ~$598, reg $833](https://myernk.com/fr/products/iluminage-at-home-skin-smoothing-anti-aging-laser-fda-cleared)): describes it as a **non-ablative *fractional* laser**, **1440nm band**, **380 mJ (low) / 500 mJ (high)**, **\"36 light spots per second\"**, **12 min/session every 3 days**, no cooling mentioned. Claims: fine lines, pores, acne scars, uneven tone, spots; clinical 78%/87%/95% fine-line improvement at 2/4/12 weeks. Ships from US warehouse; **cannot ship outside the USA**. Seller = myernk (HK), the same reseller that lists YDUNVIE Iris Ice.\n- **The discrepancy to resolve:** the FDA record (non-fractional, 3–4 J/cm² over a 7mm spot) and the retail listing (fractional, mJ-per-spot, 36 spots/s) **don't match**. Either the listing is marketing spin on the bulk K133473 device, or it's a newer/different (possibly relabeled) fractional unit sold under the Iluminage name. **Unit check:** if \"380–500 mJ\" is the *total across 36 spots*, that's ~10.5–13.9 mJ/microbeam — squarely in the Tria/Clear+Brilliant fractional range; if it's per-spot, it's implausibly high. Force the seller to clarify (see [06 RFQ](06_sourcing_rfq_templates.md)).\n- **Verdict:** same wavelength family as C+B Original. **If genuinely fractional at ~10–14 mJ/microbeam, it jumps to ★★★** and becomes a real Tria FRX alternative (notably *without* cooling — a downside for pigment-prone skin). If it's the bulk K133473 device, it stays ★★. Verify the fractional claim + which K-number it actually ships under before buying. **US-only shipping** is a hard constraint.\n\n### LYMA Laser / PRO — LLLT/photobiomodulation, not resurfacing ★\n- ✅ **FDA:** K210823 / K243330 (LYMA Life, UK). **808nm NIR + 620nm red, 62.5 mW/cm², 8 cm²**. Predicates are LED/LLLT devices.\n- **Verdict:** photobiomodulation — gentle, no downtime, general skin quality. A *different category* from fractional resurfacing despite premium \"laser\" marketing.\n\n### JOVS masks (Shenzhen Qianyu) — VCSEL PBM ★\n- ✅ **FDA:** K244020 (JM1/JM2B) **660 + 850nm VCSEL**, 40–100 mW/cm². Also IPL hair-removal clearances (K214113, K220645).\n- **Verdict:** wearable PBM/red-light, not resurfacing.\n\n### DermRays Revive (Wuhan Lotuxs) — 1064nm, wrong category ★\n- ✅ **FDA:** K231910. **1064nm diode, 400ms, 5–10 J/cm², 15mm spot, prescription use.** For wrinkles + hair removal.\n- **Verdict:** different wavelength (targets via different mechanism), and **Rx not OTC** — not a Clear + Brilliant analog.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Professional / clinical relatives (context for \"what efficacious looks like\")\n\n| Device | Wavelength | Role |\n|--------|-----------|------|\n| Clear + Brilliant Original / Perméa | 1440 / 1927nm | entry-level in-office NAF (the benchmark) |\n| Sciton **Moxi** | 1927nm | clinic pigment/tone/prevention NAF |\n| **LaseMD / LaseMD Ultra** | 1927nm thulium | clinic pigment + topical-delivery microchannels |\n| **Fraxel re:store / Dual** | 1550 / 1927nm | the higher-power origin of the category |\n| Cynosure **Affirm** | 1440 / 1320nm | clinic NAF wrinkle/pigment |\n\nThese define the upper bound. Home devices are deliberately a fraction of these — useful for calibrating expectations.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Final ranking for the user's goals\n\n**For pigment / PIH / brightness (1927nm physics):**\n1. *In-office:* Clear + Brilliant **Perméa** / Sciton Moxi / LaseMD\n2. *At-home:* **YDUNVIE Dora (1927nm)** ⚠️ — verify specs/authorization\n3. *Reality check:* topicals + SPF still beat any home laser on pigment (see parent [07](../01_ipl_hair_removal/07_alternatives_and_strategy.md))\n\n**For collagen / texture / pores / fine lines (1450nm physics):**\n1. *In-office:* Clear + Brilliant **Original** / Fraxel\n2. *At-home, trustworthy:* **Tria FRX** ✅ (FDA-cleared, real company)\n3. *At-home, China-market:* **YDUNVIE Iris Ice / Iris Ice Plus** ⚠️ (or MimiSilk Iris) — verify\n4. *Gentle maintenance:* **NIRA** ✅ (non-fractional)\n\n**The \"forgotten\" devices worth studying:** **PaloVia** and **Philips RéAura** — the two purest home-Fraxel devices ever sold (both discontinued).\n\n---\n\n### Sources\n- [Tria FAN K130459](https://www.accessdata.fda.gov/cdrh_docs/pdf13/k130459.pdf) · [NIRA Model 2 K222685](https://www.accessdata.fda.gov/cdrh_docs/pdf22/K222685.pdf) · [NIRA Model 1 K163137](https://www.accessdata.fda.gov/cdrh_docs/pdf16/K163137.pdf)\n- [PaloVia / Palomar LOI multicenter trial](https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0190962212001430) · [Lasers turn back time (RéAura 1435nm + Solta)](https://www.electrooptics.com/feature/lasers-turn-back-time)\n- [Jiangsu Unimed K182498 (FDA 510k DB)](https://www.accessdata.fda.gov/scripts/cdrh/cfdocs/cfpmn/pmn.cfm?ID=K182498) · [MimiSilk Iris product page](https://www.mimisilk.com/products/mimisilk-iris-1450nm-advanced-skin-renewing-device)\n- [myernk — Iluminage At-Home Skin Smoothing Laser listing (~$598)](https://myernk.com/fr/products/iluminage-at-home-skin-smoothing-anti-aging-laser-fda-cleared) · Iluminage FDA: K133473 (Cynosure)\n- [Clear + Brilliant Touch protocol NCT05027282](https://clinicaltrials.gov/study/NCT05027282)\n", "file": "03_device_landscape.md"}, {"id": "doc4", "md": "# Suppliers & Companies Making These Devices\n\nWho actually builds the home/clinic fractional & non-ablative lasers — the companies, the China supply chain, the FDA-record map, where they sell, and what they cost. Confidence: ✅ verified / ⚠️ claim / 🔍 inferred.\n\n---\n\n## 1. The headline company: Jiangsu Unimed / YDUNVIE / 易科美 / Olemy (欧莱美)\n\nThis is the single most important lead for an actual *home* 1450nm fractional laser — and the likely manufacturer behind several Western-branded \"Iris\" devices.\n\n### Identity / alias map\n| Alias | What it is | Source |\n|-------|-----------|--------|\n| **易科美 / YDUNVIE** | consumer brand | 36Kr company profile; ydunvie.com.cn |\n| **江苏欧莱美激光科技有限公司 / Jiangsu Unimed Laser Science & Technology Ltd.** | the company (English name used publicly) | ✅ 36Kr; iF Design |\n| **无锡欧莱美激光科技有限公司 / Wuxi Olemy Laser Technology** | related corporate entity (Wuxi/Jiangyin, Jiangsu) | Chinese product pages |\n| **合铼科技** | parent/incubator/financing entity tied to the brand | 36Kr |\n| **Jiangsu Unimed Laser Technology Co., Ltd.** | ✅ **FDA 510(k) K182498** applicant — \"Advanced Skin Renewing Device,\" product code **ONG** (powered laser w/ microbeam/fractional output), cleared **Nov 30, 2018** | ✅ FDA DB |\n\n**Why it matters:** ✅ K182498 is exactly the right FDA category (microbeam/fractional laser). 36Kr describes 易科美 as a home-laser-beauty-device developer covering skincare, skin detection, hair, gum, and body/pain, with wavelengths ~650nm–1927nm and \"40+\" products. This is a **real, relatively sophisticated company**, not a generic LED-mask seller — and the strongest candidate factory behind **MimiSilk Iris**, **OYAY Iris**, and **myernk's** \"YDUNVIE Ice Crystal\" device.\n\n### Where YDUNVIE sells & what it costs (China)\nThe flagship consumer product is the **A9 \"ICE\" / 冰晶点阵激光美容仪** (ice-crystal fractional laser, 1450nm).\n\n> 💱 *¥/RMB figures show an approximate USD conversion at **~¥7.2 / $1** (mid-2026); ballpark only.*\n\n| Channel | Notes |\n|---------|-------|\n| **JD / 京东** | YDUNVIE brand pages; promo listings low-¥3,000s (≈$415+) |\n| **Tmall / 天猫 (易科美旗舰店)** | flagship store; A9 with coupon pricing |\n| **SMZDM / 什么值得买** | deal tracking — A9 ~¥2,788 (≈$387), \"常卖价\" ~¥3,388 (≈$471), list ~¥4,588 (≈$637), historical low ~¥1,396 (≈$194) |\n| **Douyin / 抖音** | marketed for acne marks, pores, texture, collagen |\n| **Cross-border resellers** | myernk (HK), HALOHK, Jofiou, GlamGlobal (UK), Dealmoon-indexed A7-Iris (¥5,982 ≈ $831) |\n\n> **Note on myernk:** beyond YDUNVIE Iris Ice, myernk also lists an [**Iluminage At-Home Skin Smoothing Laser** (~$598, US-only shipping)](https://myernk.com/fr/products/iluminage-at-home-skin-smoothing-anti-aging-laser-fda-cleared) — claimed 1440nm non-ablative *fractional*, 380/500 mJ, 36 spots/s. This **conflicts with** the Iluminage FDA record (K133473, Cynosure: non-fractional, 3–4 J/cm², 7mm spot). Treat the fractional claim as unverified and ask which K-number it ships under. See [03 device landscape](03_device_landscape.md).\n\n**Fair China benchmark price: ~¥3,000–¥3,400 RMB** (≈ $420–$470) for the A9/ICE, unless a verified promo. Western relabels sell higher: myernk YDUNVIE Iris Ice ~$580; MimiSilk Iris ~$599; OYAY Iris Ice Plus ~$999.\n\n### Alibaba match? — No clean one\nThere is **no trustworthy exact Alibaba listing** for the YDUNVIE A9/ICE handheld. The closest results are *not* the same product:\n- \"1450nm Accu Smart Acne Toning System\" — Korean/pro acne system, wrong form factor\n- 1927nm thulium NAF lasers — different wavelength, clinic standing machines\n- CO₂ fractional listings — ablative clinic gear, unrelated\n\n**Implication:** this is a **brand-controlled consumer device**, not an open white-label Alibaba SKU. To source it, go through YDUNVIE/Jiangsu Unimed directly or an authorized agent — and demand an authorization letter.\n\n### Contact / search terms\n`江苏欧莱美激光科技有限公司` · `Jiangsu Unimed Laser Science and Technology` · `YDUNVIE 易科美 1450nm 点阵激光美容仪` · `合铼科技 易科美` · site: ydunvie.com.cn\n\n---\n\n## 2. Chinese suppliers — professional / OEM (similar tech, mostly clinic-grade)\n\n| Supplier | Location | Makes | Closeness to a home fractional laser |\n|----------|----------|-------|--------------------------------------|\n| **Focuslight Technologies** | Xi'an (public: SSE STAR 688167) | 1470nm **diode laser modules/subassemblies** for home skin rejuvenation | ★★★★ best **OEM component** source; publishes a home 1470nm NAF module (1.5W, 6–12 mJ/spot, single/multi/dot-matrix). **B2B only — not a finished-device seller.** See §2a. |\n| **Gigaalaser / GigaaMedical** | Wuhan | 1470nm NAF diode (Cheese Plus: 1470±20nm, 4W, dot-matrix); THEIA 1550+1927nm | ★★★ very relevant tech, but **pro/salon**, not handheld home |\n| **Guangzhou Huafei Liton** | Guangzhou | 1927nm thulium + 1550/1927 dual-wave fractional machines; OEM/ODM | ★★ Moxi/LaseMD/Fraxel-class clinic gear |\n| **Beijing HONKON Technologies** | Beijing | 1927nm thulium fractional machines | ★★ pro device maker |\n| **Zhengzhou PZ Laser Slim** | Zhengzhou | 1927nm thulium (\"Lavandula\"-style) | ★★ salon/pro |\n| **Shandong Huamei Technology** | Shandong | 1927nm thulium fractional | ★★ salon/pro |\n| **Hebei Keylaser Sci-Tech** | Hebei | 1927nm thulium / NAF systems | ★★ salon/pro |\n| **Beijing Superlaser Technology** | Beijing | 1927nm thulium NAF/sub-ablative; OEM/ODM | ★★ salon/pro |\n| **Shanghai Apolo Medical** | Shanghai | 1550nm erbium-fiber fractional (claims CE/ISO/FDA K221770) | ★★ Fraxel-1550-class clinic |\n\n**Takeaway:** for a true *home handheld*, the realistic China paths are **(1) Jiangsu Unimed/YDUNVIE** (finished device) or **(2) Focuslight** (commission an OEM build around its 1470nm module). The rest sell **clinic machines**, not consumer units.\n\n### 2a. What exactly is Focuslight? (you asked — not a splash page) ✅\n\n**Focuslight Technologies Inc.** is a **large, publicly-traded photonics company** — not a marketing page, and not a beauty brand.\n- Founded **2007** (Dr. Victor X. Liu), HQ **Xi'an, China**; **publicly listed on the Shanghai Stock Exchange STAR Market (688167)** since its Dec-2021 IPO.\n- **900+ employees** across China, Germany, Switzerland, Singapore, Malaysia; **400+ patents**; ISO 9001/14001/45001 + IATF 16949. Grew via acquisitions of **LIMO GmbH (2017)** and **SUSS MicroOptics (2024)**.\n- Core business: **high-power diode-laser components, modules, and micro-optics** (photon generation + photon control) for optical comms, semiconductor, advanced manufacturing, automotive, medical, etc.\n\n**Their relationship to beauty devices — they're a *component supplier to manufacturers*, B2B only:**\n- The skin-rejuvenation page offers a **\"home-use laser skin rejuvenation module\"**: **1470nm non-ablative fractional**, eye-safe, customizable **single-spot / multi-spot / dot-matrix** output (≈1.5 W, 6–12 mJ/spot), plus a beam-homogenizer/flat-top optic.\n- **No pricing, no MOQ, no \"buy now,\" no consumer sales.** The page's only CTA is *\"contact our sales teams.\"*\n\n**So, directly answering you:**\n- *Splash page?* **No** — real public company.\n- *Do they supply beauty-laser companies?* **Yes** — they sell the **laser engine/module** that a device maker (e.g. a YDUNVIE-type brand) would build a finished handheld around.\n- *Can you buy direct?* **Not a finished device.** You'd engage their **sales/OEM** team to source **modules** and commission a build — realistic only if you're manufacturing a product, not buying one unit. For a single consumer device, go to **YDUNVIE/MimiSilk** instead; Focuslight matters only if you want to **build your own**.\n\n---\n\n## 3. The FDA 510(k) supplier map (better than Alibaba for tracing the real maker)\n\n> **Caveat:** FDA records show the **510(k) applicant / brand owner**, not always the contract manufacturer or component factory. Treat consultants and predicates as *investigation leads*, not proof.\n\n### Confirmed FDA applicants / likely OEMs\n| Device / brand | 510(k) | Applicant (likely real owner) | Tech |\n|----------------|--------|------------------------------|------|\n| NIRA Skin (Model 1) | K163137 | **Dermal Photonics Corp** (Danvers, MA) | 1450nm non-fractional |\n| NIRA Model 2 / Pro | K222685 | Dermal Photonics Corp | 1450±20nm, 2W, 2.1–3.8 J/cm² |\n| Tria FAN | K130459 | **Tria Beauty, Inc.** (Dublin, CA) | 1450±50nm fractional |\n| Tria FANp | K141868 | Tria Beauty, Inc. | 1450±50nm fractional |\n| PaloVia / Palomar LOI | K090525 | **Palomar Medical** | 1410nm fractional |\n| Iluminage Skin Smoothing | K133473 | **Cynosure Inc.** | 1440nm, 3–4 J/cm² |\n| **MimiSilk Iris** (≈ YDUNVIE Iris) | **K182498** | **Jiangsu Unimed Laser** (Jiangyin, China) | \"Advanced Skin Renewing Device,\" microbeam/fractional — **near-confirmed: MimiSilk's product name matches the K182498 device name verbatim** |\n| DermRays Revive | K231910 | **Wuhan Lotuxs Technology** | 1064nm Rx laser |\n| JOVS mask (JM1/JM2B) | K244020 | **Shenzhen Qianyu Technology** | 660/850nm VCSEL |\n| JOVS IPL (Graphene / hair) | K214113 / K220645 | Shenzhen Qianyu Technology | IPL hair removal |\n| LYMA Laser / PRO | K210823 / K243330 | **LYMA Life Ltd.** (UK) | 808+620nm LLLT |\n\n### Regulatory consultants (who filed the paperwork — useful for ecosystem mapping)\n- **Feiying Drug & Medical Consulting** → Qianyu/JOVS K244020\n- **Guangzhou Tianke Testing** → JOVS IPL filings\n- **RQM+** → LYMA Laser PRO\n- **Acknowledge Regulatory Strategies (Allison Komiyama)** → LYMA Laser K210823\n- Dermal Photonics and Jiangsu Unimed appear to **self-file**.\n\n### Predicate companies (the technology family tree)\nPalomar/LOI (root predicate for NIRA + Tria) · Cynosure (Iluminage, Affirm, Elite+) · Solta/Fraxel + Reliant Technologies · Photo Therapeutics (Omnilux) · Light Biosciences (GentleWaves) · LightStim · Carol Cole (Trinity) · Light Tree Ventures (Q-Rejuvalight) · CyDen (SmoothSkin Gold). *Investigate-further lead:* Shenzhen JVK Medical (named in a JOVS predicate table; FDA applicant of record is Qianyu).\n\n### Customs/import leads (lower confidence than FDA)\n- NIRA / Dermal Photonics → Acme Circuit (India, PCB), Dongguan Essentia (housings), Shenzhen Rihuida (power adapters)\n- Tria Beauty → Benchmark Electronics Thailand (historical, hair-removal line)\n\n---\n\n## 4. Who to contact first\n\n**For an actual home fractional device:**\n1. **Jiangsu Unimed / YDUNVIE / 易科美** — finished 1450nm (Iris) and 1927nm (Dora) handhelds\n2. **Focuslight** — OEM 1470nm modules to commission a build\n\n**For a pro/clinic machine with the same tech:**\n3. **Gigaalaser** (Cheese Plus 1470, THEIA 1550/1927)\n4. **Liton / Huafei**, then HONKON, PZ, Huamei, Keylaser, Superlaser, Apolo\n\n---\n\n## 5. Screening every supplier (send after first contact)\n\n1. Are you the **manufacturer**, a trading company, or a distributor?\n2. Exact **legal manufacturer name** on the FDA/CE documents?\n3. **510(k) number** — and does it cover *this exact model* or only a similar one?\n4. Provide the **device label, IFU/manual, and UDI**.\n5. Is it **OTC/home-use** or **prescription/professional-use**?\n6. Exact output **per level**: wavelength (±nm), J/cm² **and/or** mJ/pulse, pulse width, spot size, fractional density.\n7. Is the J/cm² figure **single-pulse, pulse-train total, or full-treatment dose**? *(Same trap as the parent IPL repo — multi-pulse \"totals\" inflate headline numbers.)*\n8. Which **lab** measured the optical output? Provide the report.\n9. **Authorization letter** from the 510(k) holder for private label/export.\n\n## 6. Red flags\n- \"FDA approved\" / \"FDA registered\" with **no K-number** (registration ≠ clearance)\n- \"Medical CE\" with no notified-body/MDR detail\n- States \"1450nm laser\" but **can't give J/cm² or mJ/pulse**\n- \"High energy\" with **no pulse width, spot size, or beam profile**\n- **No contact sensor / no eye-safety (IEC 60825-1) report**\n- Home-use claims for **melasma, mole/tattoo removal, or ablative resurfacing**\n- A \"fractional\" listing that is actually **CO₂, IPL, RF, or 808nm hair removal** in disguise\n\n---\n\n### Sources\n- [Jiangsu Unimed K182498 (FDA DB)](https://www.accessdata.fda.gov/scripts/cdrh/cfdocs/cfpmn/pmn.cfm?ID=K182498)\n- [NIRA K222685](https://www.accessdata.fda.gov/cdrh_docs/pdf22/K222685.pdf) · [NIRA K163137](https://www.accessdata.fda.gov/cdrh_docs/pdf16/K163137.pdf) · [Tria FAN K130459](https://www.accessdata.fda.gov/cdrh_docs/pdf13/k130459.pdf)\n- [MimiSilk Iris](https://www.mimisilk.com/products/mimisilk-iris-1450nm-advanced-skin-renewing-device) · [myernk YDUNVIE Ice Crystal](https://myernk.com) · [Focuslight (1470nm home NAF)](https://www.focuslight.com)\n", "file": "04_suppliers_and_companies.md"}, {"id": "doc5", "md": "# YDUNVIE / 欧莱美 Full Product Catalog Analysis\n\nSource: indexed catalog pages from ydunvie.com.cn (the live .cn site was unstable during research). **~31 product names** confirmed across catalog pages.\n\n> ⚠️ **Critical caveat:** product/category *names* are confirmed from indexed catalog pages; most detailed *specs* below are **inferred from category + naming + a few retail listings**, not verified spec sheets. Treat every spec as \"demand the datasheet.\" See screening questions in [04_suppliers_and_companies §5](04_suppliers_and_companies.md).\n\n**Company:** Wuxi/Jiangsu Olemy (欧莱美) Laser Technology → brand YDUNVIE / 易科美. Per 36Kr: skincare, skin detection, hair, gum, body/pain; wavelengths ~650nm–1927nm; \"40+\" products. FDA: K182498 (microbeam/fractional). Most credible technical strength = **home fractional laser skincare** (1450nm Iris + 1927nm Dora/Velar lines).\n\n**Company facts (✅ verified this pass):**\n- Brand 易科美/YDUNVIE launched in China **April 2014**; **first domestic (China) home-use 1450nm fractional laser** beauty device.\n- Parent **合铼科技 (Helai)** raised a **tens-of-millions-RMB (≈ low-millions USD) Pre-A round** (36Kr, May 2024) — a funded, growing company, not a fly-by-night.\n\n> 💱 *All ¥/RMB figures below include an approximate USD conversion at **~¥7.2 / $1** (mid-2026). Rates move — treat as ballpark.*\n- **Three core (patented) technologies:** 纳米点阵 (nano-matrix microbeam) · 磁悬浮摆臂扫描 (magnetic-levitation scanning arm / frame-type **DynamicScan**) · 智能冷却 + 360° 环形冷凝冰晶 (intelligent cooling + 360° ring ice-crystal cooling).\n- Marketing tagline: \"院线同源\" (*same-origin as clinic devices*) / \"移动的私家美容院\" (a mobile private salon).\n\n---\n\n## 0. Model-code map (the A-series) — read this first ⭐\n\nThe retail SKUs use **A-series codes** that don't appear on the English brand pages. This is the Rosetta stone for matching listings (JD/Tmall/Lazada/MimiSilk/myernk) to actual products:\n\n| Code | Product name | Wavelength | What it is | China price | Best for |\n|------|-------------|-----------|------------|-------------|----------|\n| **A7** | **Iris** (纳米点阵嫩肤仪) | 1450nm ✅ | the **original** home fractional rejuvenation device; 360° semiconductor ice cooling, deep-dermal | ~¥3,998 (≈$555; JD ¥3,988 ≈ $554) | pores, eye wrinkles, acne scars, rough/sensitive skin, collagen |\n| **A9** | **Iris Ice / Ice Crystal** (冰晶点阵) | 1450nm ⚠️ | the **flagship/premium upgrade** — denser/higher-coverage nano-array, full 360° ice-crystal cooling + DynamicScan; aimed at **stubborn acne pits + severe pores** | ~¥2,788–4,588 (≈$387–$637; promo ~¥3,000–3,400 ≈ $417–$472) | the \"do it properly\" 1450nm collagen/texture device |\n| **A8** | **Dora / \"大白\"** (纳米点阵焕肤仪) | **1927nm** ⚠️ | the **pigment/brightening** device — point-matrix for melanin metabolism, freckles, dullness, even tone | ~¥2,300 (≈$319) China / ~$719 reseller | **pigment / PIH / brightening (your pigment goal)** |\n| **MINI** | **Iris Mini** | 1450nm 🔍 | smaller/portable fractional | ~¥2,300 (≈$319) | budget/portable texture |\n| **P5** | **Nova Plus** (三重光电祛痘) | multi-light 🔍 | triple-photoelectric acne device | ~¥1,580 (≈$219) | active acne |\n\n> ⚠️ **Naming caution:** the English \"Iris Ice **Plus**\" (seen on OYAY/MimiSilk-adjacent listings) and the Chinese **A9 Iris Ice** may or may not be the exact same SKU — \"Plus\"/\"Pro\" suffixes on export listings often denote a region/bundle/firmware variant, not a hardware step-up (per [03](03_device_landscape.md), Iris and Iris Ice both cap ~12 mJ/pulse). **Confirm the A-code + spec sheet before assuming a \"Plus\" is stronger.**\n\n**The short version for your decision:** the device you most likely want for **collagen/texture** is the **A9 Iris Ice (1450nm)**; for **pigment** it's the **A8 Dora (1927nm)**. MimiSilk sells the **1450nm Iris** (see §G) — *not*, as far as I can tell, a 1927nm Dora.\n\n---\n\n## A. Tender Skin / 嫩肤 — the 1450nm fractional collagen/texture line ⭐ most relevant\n\n| Model | Likely role | Confidence | Notes |\n|-------|-------------|-----------|-------|\n| **Iris** *(A7)* | original 1450nm nano-fractional | ⚠️ | 360° semiconductor ice cooling, deep-dermal; ~¥3,998 (≈$555). The base model MimiSilk appears to resell (§G). |\n| **Iris Ice** *(A9)* | **flagship** 1450nm nano-matrix fractional w/ cooling | ⚠️ best-documented | 180 J full-face, DynamicScan, ~1.1 µm dot spacing, 133 ms pulses, 3 modes, \"Smart Cool\" ~6 s, depth ~300/350/400 µm, ~10 min full-face, 3 treatments/charge. **The flagship to care about.** |\n| **Iris FR** | fractional-rejuvenation variant | 🔍 name only | \"FR\" likely fractional resurfacing; ask wavelength/cooling/energy/depth |\n| **Iris Ice Plus** | export \"upgrade\" of Iris Ice | ⚠️ | 3–12 mJ/pulse; **probably not stronger** — upgrades look like cooling/sensors/app/zones/cert, not raw output (both cap ~12 mJ). May just be a region/bundle label for A9. |\n| **Iris Mini** *(MINI)* | smaller/portable | 🔍 | ~¥2,300 (≈$319); likely lower energy / slower full-face |\n| **R10** | skin-rejuv device | 🔍 generic name | confirm modality (1450/1927/LED/RF?) before assuming |\n| **R10 RS** | revised R10 | 🔍 | \"unknown but newer\"; get datasheet |\n| **Muse** | 纳米点阵嫩肤 (nano-fractional) | ⚠️ | if truly 1450nm nano-fractional, overlaps Iris; differentiator = energy/cooling/scan/time |\n\n**Targets for this line:** pores, texture, oiliness, acne marks, early fine lines, shallow pitted marks, collagen. **Best fit for the collagen/texture goal.**\n\n---\n\n## B. Skin Renewal / 焕肤 — the 1927nm pigment/brightening line ⭐ most relevant for *pigment*\n\n| Model | Likely role | Confidence | Notes |\n|-------|-------------|-----------|-------|\n| **Dora** *(A8 / \"大白\")* | base 1927nm renewal/brightening | ⚠️ | **1927nm point-matrix laser**, melanin metabolism, freckles, dullness, even tone; 3 gears, 2–3×/week, 20–25 min/session, inductive charging, vibration, \"cherry-blossom pink\"; ~¥2,300 (≈$319) China / **~$719 reseller**, 1-yr warranty. **Home Perméa/Moxi analog.** |\n| **Dora Plus** | upgraded Dora | 🔍 | more modes / energy / cooling? |\n| **Dora Pro** | top-end Dora | 🔍 | most interesting for **pigment/brightness** if 1927nm confirmed |\n\n> ⚠️ **The recurring Dora wavelength inconsistency:** retail copy headlines \"1927nm\" but some body text says \"1450nm.\" Likely sloppy copy reuse from the Iris template — but **this is the single most important spec to confirm for your pigment goal.** A real 1927nm = correct pigment physics; if it's actually 1450nm it's just another collagen device. Demand the rating label / spec sheet before buying.\n\n**Targets:** pigment, PIH, dullness, uneven tone, brightening — **best wavelength match for the user's pigment goal.** Caution: 1927nm can worsen PIH if poorly dosed.\n\n---\n\n## C. Wrinkle Reduction\n| Model | Likely role | Confidence |\n|-------|-------------|-----------|\n| **Zen** | dedicated fine-line device | 🔍 modality unknown (laser? IR? RF? LED?) — ask wavelength/fluence/depth |\n\n---\n\n## D. Whitening / Brightening (7 products)\n| Model | Likely role | Notes |\n|-------|-------------|-------|\n| **Velar Precision** | targeted spot/brightening | small window for spots/freckles — verify source (1927? LED? VCSEL?) |\n| **Velar Max** | wider/stronger brightening | \"Max\" ≠ proven higher fluence — ask energy + area |\n| **Velar Light** | entry-level brightening | gentler, maintenance |\n| **Velar Smooth** | brightening + texture-smoothing | may overlap 1927nm renewal |\n| **VCSEL Light** | VCSEL-based light | more \"laser-like\" than LED, gentler than fractional; ask wavelength/coherence/target |\n| **Velar Mask** | wearable brightening mask | lower-risk, lower-power |\n| **LED Mask** | LED mask | least aggressive; good for redness/inflammation/acne support, **weak for true pigment removal** |\n\n---\n\n## E. Acne (4 products)\n| Model | Likely role | Notes |\n|-------|-------------|-------|\n| **Nova** | base acne device (iF Design: \"Advance Acne Clearing Device\") | ask wavelength: ~415nm blue (C. acnes), ~630–660nm red (inflammation), NIR (healing) |\n| **Nova Plus** | \"三重光电祛痘\" (triple photoelectric) | more serious than single-LED wand; ask the 3 modalities |\n| **Nova Pro** | higher-end | verify acne type targeted |\n| **Nova Max** | highest-power/largest-area | safety docs matter if heat/laser-based |\n\n---\n\n## F. Other categories (lower priority for skin-quality goal)\n| Category | Models | What they likely are |\n|----------|--------|----------------------|\n| **Penetration** | Iontop H | iontophoresis / active-ingredient delivery (companion, not resurfacing) |\n| **Pain Relief** | Relax Light, Relax Smooth | likely 830nm IR / photobiomodulation; ask mW/cm² + J/cm² |\n| **Hair Removal** | Remo Max / Light / Smooth / Precision | likely IPL; judge by J/cm², filter, pulse width, cooling, skin-tone sensor |\n| **Hair Regrowth** | Reju Max / Precision / Light | red-light/laser scalp therapy; ask wavelength, diode count, output, format |\n| **Gum Protection** | Rete Precision | oral/gum photobiomodulation — needs dental regulatory docs |\n| **Desktop / Pro** | Premium A | multifunction platform — confirm home vs salon vs medical |\n| **Oral platform** | Smile Clear | multifunction oral/teeth/gum laser platform |\n| **Skin analysis** | AI Derma Mirror | AI skin-analysis camera (diagnostic, **not treatment**) — for salon/retail demos |\n\n---\n\n## G. Is MimiSilk just a rebranded YDUNVIE? — and how to buy\n\n**MimiSilk Iris (✅ specs pulled this pass):** 1450nm, **12 mJ single-beam max** (\"~¼ of clinical-equipment energy\"), **100 µm × 30 µm microbeam**, targets dermis ~300–600 µm (acne marks ≤200 µm), **5–10 min full-face**, **$599** (reg $699), **2-yr warranty + 90-day money-back**, ships to US/CA/AU/EU + selected Asia. Claims \"FDA-Cleared\" (**no K-number given**), self-describes as **\"MimiSilk (Danish beauty science).\"**\n\n**The verdict on the rebrand question:**\n- The **spec fingerprint is essentially identical to the YDUNVIE Iris (A7)**: same 1450nm, same ~12 mJ ceiling, same 100 µm microbeam, same fractional acne-mark/pore/fine-line indications. That's a strong match — consistent with the Reddit/myernk trail that MimiSilk = a relabeled YDUNVIE/Jiangsu Unimed device.\n- **BUT** MimiSilk's own page shows **zero** YDUNVIE / Jiangsu Unimed / China references and markets itself as **\"Danish.\"** So the link is *inferred from spec-matching*, not disclosed. 🔍\n- **What MimiSilk corresponds to:** the **1450nm Iris (A7)** — *not* clearly the premium **A9 Iris Ice**, and **not** a **1927nm Dora**. MimiSilk lists only a 1450nm device (alone or bundled with PDRN masks). **If you want the 1927nm pigment device, MimiSilk likely can't supply it.**\n\n**Two purchase paths (per your plan):**\n\n| Path | Pros | Cons | Best when |\n|------|------|------|-----------|\n| **Direct from manufacturer** (Jiangsu Unimed / YDUNVIE / 易科美) | full model range incl. **A9 Iris Ice** *and* **A8 Dora 1927nm**; lowest unit price (~¥3,000–3,400 ≈ $417–$472); can request real spec sheet + K-number | MOQ/import/language friction; warranty/returns harder; must verify authorization | you want the **1927nm Dora**, the true **A9**, or multiple units / OEM |\n| **MimiSilk** (Western storefront) | English support, **2-yr warranty + 90-day money-back**, ships to US/EU/etc., turnkey | **~$599** (premium over China); only the **1450nm Iris**; \"Danish\" claim obscures origin; **no K-number disclosed** | you want the **1450nm collagen/texture device** with hassle-free returns and don't need 1927nm |\n\n**Before buying either, get in writing:** (1) the **A-code** of the exact unit, (2) **wavelength on the rating label** (critical for Dora — confirm 1927nm), (3) the **FDA K-number** it ships under (likely K182498) and whether it covers *that* model, (4) mJ/pulse vs full-face-J clarified, (5) cooling spec, (6) Fitzpatrick/skin-tone limits. See [06 RFQ](06_sourcing_rfq_templates.md).\n\n> **For your stated goals:** if pigment is the priority → you need the **A8 Dora (1927nm)**, which means **manufacturer-direct** (MimiSilk doesn't sell it). If collagen/texture is the priority → **MimiSilk Iris** (≈ A7) is the low-friction buy, or **A9 Iris Ice** direct if you want the denser flagship.\n\n---\n\n## Channel & price summary (1450nm Iris family)\n\n| Channel | Product | Price | Notes |\n|---------|---------|-------|-------|\n| China retail (JD/Tmall/SMZDM) | A9 Iris Ice / A7 Iris | ¥2,788–4,588 (≈$387–$637; promo ~¥3,000–3,400 ≈ $417–$472) | cheapest; domestic |\n| Dealmoon (cross-border) | A7-Iris | ¥5,982 (≈$831) / CA$3,988 | indexed export |\n| myernk (HK, \"authorized agent\") | YDUNVIE Ice Crystal | ~$580 | + also lists Iluminage (see [03](03_device_landscape.md)) |\n| MimiSilk | Iris (1450nm) | $599 (reg $699) | 2-yr warranty, 90-day refund, Western support |\n| OYAY | Iris Ice Plus | $999 | dropship; avoid unless authorization proven |\n| jofioubeauty | A8 Dora \"大白\" (1927nm) | ~$719 | a reseller path for the **pigment** device |\n\n---\n\n## Priorities for the user's goals\n1. **Dora / Dora Plus / Dora Pro (1927nm) = A8** — best wavelength for **pigment/PIH/brightening** (manufacturer-direct or jofiou; **not** MimiSilk)\n2. **Iris Ice = A9 (1450nm)** (or base **Iris = A7** via MimiSilk; also Muse / Iris FR) — best for **pores/texture/acne marks/fine lines/collagen**\n3. **Nova Plus / Pro / Max** — if active acne/post-acne inflammation is a concern\n4. *Deprioritize:* LED/VCSEL masks (maintenance only), and all Remo/Reju/Relax/Rete/Smile/Premium/AI-Mirror lines for this goal\n\n**Before buying anything from this catalog, get a spec sheet with:** exact wavelength ±tol, laser/LED type, mJ/pulse and/or J/cm² (and whether single-pulse or total), spot size, fractional density, pulse width, cooling temp, treatment depth, eye-safety design, Fitzpatrick limits, certifications (K-number/CE/IEC 60825-1/60601/ISO 13485), clinical data, contraindications.\n\n---\n\n### Sources\n- [36Kr/QQ: 「易科美」first domestic home 1450nm fractional laser; Pre-A funding (May 2024)](https://news.qq.com/rain/a/20240527A02UCJ00) · [易科美 Baidu Baike](https://baike.baidu.com/item/%E6%98%93%E7%A7%91%E7%BE%8E/22948298)\n- [美容仪之家 YDUNVIE Iris spec page (A7, ¥3,998 ≈ $555; lists MINI, A8, P5)](https://www.imeirongyi.com/product/information/ydunvie-iris.html) · [Zhihu \"院线同源易科美冰晶\" review](https://zhuanlan.zhihu.com/p/663240311)\n- [Lazada: Ydunvie **A9** Ice Crystal Dot Matrix Laser](https://www.lazada.sg/products/ydunvie-a9-ice-crystal-dot-matrix-laser-beauty-meter-ipl-device-shrink-pores-flat-pox-pits-light-acne-marks-ydunvie-i3209669909.html) · [Dealmoon A7-Iris (¥5,982 ≈ $831)](https://www.dealmoon.com/product/-ydunvie-a7-iris/3541987)\n- [jofioubeauty: Ydunvie **A8** 大白/Dora 1927nm ($719)](https://www.jofioubeauty.com/zh-usa/products/ydunvie-%E6%98%93%E7%A7%91%E7%BE%8E%E5%A4%A7%E7%99%BD%E7%B4%8D%E7%B1%B3%E9%9B%B7%E5%B0%84%E6%BF%80%E5%85%89%E7%85%A5%E8%86%9A%E5%84%80-%E5%8E%BB%E9%9B%80%E6%96%91-%E7%BE%8E%E7%99%BD%E6%8F%90%E4%BA%AE%E5%AE%B6%E7%94%A8%E7%BE%8E%E5%AE%B9%E5%84%80-1) · [MimiSilk Iris ($599)](https://www.mimisilk.com/products/mimisilk-iris-1450nm-advanced-skin-renewing-device)\n- iF Design Award (YDUNVIE devices); SMZDM/Tmall/JD listings (retail specs ⚠️ unverified)\n", "file": "05_ydunvie_catalog.md"}, {"id": "doc6", "md": "# Sourcing: RFQ Templates & Spec Sheet\n\nCopy-paste RFQs for contacting suppliers. **Do not post \"high intensity face laser\"** — bad suppliers will pitch unsafe or fake-power devices. Use the precise wording below.\n\n> **Regulatory note:** in the US, aesthetic/medical laser devices fall under both FDA radiation-emitting-product rules *and* medical-device rules depending on intended use. Ask for the actual **510(k) number**, not \"FDA registered.\"\n\n**Post two RFQs** for what the user wants: one for **1450nm fractional** (Tria/MimiSilk/PaloVia-like, the collagen/texture target) and one for **1927nm fractional** (Dora/Perméa-like, the pigment target).\n\n---\n\n## The universal spec sheet (require this from every supplier, same units)\n\n```\nExact wavelength and tolerance: ___ nm ± ___ nm\nLaser type: Diode / VCSEL / fiber / other\nFractional or non-fractional: ___\nFluence if non-fractional: ___ J/cm² at each level\nPulse energy if fractional: ___ mJ/pulse at each level\nPulse width / pulse train: ___ ms or ___ sec\nSpot size / beam size: ___ mm² or ___ cm²\nBeam profile: Gaussian / top-hat / other\nFractional microbeam diameter: ___ µm\nFractional density / coverage: ___ % or ___ beams/cm²\nRepetition rate: ___ Hz\nCooling method: fan / contact cooling / sapphire / none\nContact sensor: yes/no\nSkin contact lockout: yes/no\nSkin tone sensor: yes/no\nEye safety design: describe\nTreatment area: face / periorbital / full face / body\nBattery / power: USB-C / adapter / rechargeable\nCartridge or lifetime: ___ pulses / hours\nWarranty: ___ months\n```\n\n**Unit trap to police:** make them state whether each J/cm² or mJ figure is **single-pulse, pulse-train total, or full-treatment dose.** (Same multi-pulse inflation issue as the parent IPL repo's T055/T023 finding.)\n\n---\n\n## RFQ #1 — 1450nm fractional (collagen/texture; Tria/MimiSilk/PaloVia-like)\n\n**Title:** OEM/ODM handheld 1450nm non-ablative diode laser skin rejuvenation device with FDA 510(k), IEC 60825-1, IEC 60601 reports\n\n> We are sourcing a qualified OEM/ODM manufacturer of a **handheld non-ablative diode laser** skin-rejuvenation device for wrinkle reduction / texture improvement.\n>\n> **Target:** wavelength **1410–1450nm** (esp. 1450nm ±20–50nm); handheld diode; **home-use/OTC preferred** (or clearly-labeled professional). Both technology options welcome: **(a) fractional 1410–1450nm** (Tria/PaloVia/advanced-skin-renewing class) or **(b) non-fractional 1450nm** (NIRA/Iluminage class).\n>\n> Please complete the **universal spec sheet** above for every model, and provide:\n> - FDA **510(k) number** + applicant name + **authorization letter** to private-label/export\n> - FDA device listing + establishment registration (if applicable)\n> - **IEC 60825-1** (laser safety), **IEC 60601-1** (electrical), **IEC 60601-1-2** (EMC), **IEC 60601-1-11** (home healthcare, if home-use), **IEC 60601-2-22** (laser equipment, if applicable)\n> - **ISO 10993** biocompatibility (skin-contact parts), **ISO 13485**, **ISO 14971** risk file, **IEC 62366** usability, software validation (if applicable), CE/MDR, UKCA, RoHS, REACH, FCC\n> - Device **label photo, IFU/manual**, and a **video of output measured on a calibrated meter**\n>\n> **Do not send generic \"FDA registered\" certificates.** Quote: sample price, MOQ, OEM/private-label cost, mold/shell cost, lead time, packaging, warranty.\n\n**Reasonable benchmarks (✅):** NIRA Model 2 (K222685) is the cleanest *non-fractional* model: 1450±20nm, spot 12.5×13.8mm², 2W, fluence 2.1–3.8 J/cm². Tria FAN (K130459) is the *fractional* benchmark: 1450±50nm, periorbital.\n\n---\n\n## RFQ #2 — 1927nm fractional (pigment/brightening; Dora/Perméa-like)\n\n**Title:** OEM/ODM handheld 1927nm non-ablative fractional laser for pigment/brightening with FDA/IEC files\n\n> We are sourcing a **handheld 1927nm non-ablative fractional laser** for superficial pigment, dullness, and tone (home-use/OTC preferred).\n>\n> **Target:** 1927nm ±20nm, fractional microbeam output, contact/\"ice\" cooling, consumer handheld form factor (similar category to Clear+Brilliant Perméa / Sciton Moxi at a home dose).\n>\n> Complete the **universal spec sheet**, with special attention to: mJ/pulse per level, microbeam diameter, density, **treatment depth**, cooling temperature, and **Fitzpatrick/skin-tone restrictions** (pigment devices can worsen PIH). Provide the same regulatory package as RFQ #1.\n\n---\n\n## RFQ #3 — separate category: 1064nm higher-fluence (NOT a C+B analog — only if exploring)\n\n**Title:** OEM/ODM 1064nm handheld diode laser (wrinkle/hair) with verified J/cm², pulse width, FDA/IEC files\n\n> 1064nm handheld laser for wrinkle treatment and/or hair removal. Provide wavelength±, J/cm² per level, pulse width, spot size, cooling, **Rx vs OTC status**, Fitzpatrick support, eye-safety class, interlocks, FDA 510(k), IEC 60825-1 / 60601-2-22 reports.\n\n**Benchmark (✅):** DermRays Revive (K231910): 1064±10nm, 400ms, 5–10 J/cm², 15mm spot — **prescription**, not OTC. So explicitly confirm Rx-vs-OTC.\n\n---\n\n## RFQ #4 — separate category: VCSEL/LLLT (JOVS/LYMA-like, gentle PBM)\n\n**Title:** OEM/ODM VCSEL / low-level laser photobiomodulation facial device with mW/cm² report + FDA/IEC files\n\n> PBM facial device (VCSEL/laser-diode/LED). Provide wavelengths (660/808/850nm…), irradiance mW/cm², treatment time, area, calculated J/cm² dose, emitter count, eye-safety class, FDA 510(k), IEC 60825-1, IEC 60601-1/EMC, biocompatibility.\n\n**Benchmarks (✅):** JOVS/Qianyu mask (K244020): 660/850nm VCSEL, 40–100 mW/cm². LYMA (K210823): 808+620nm, 62.5 mW/cm², 8 cm².\n\n---\n\n## Supplier screening questions (send after first reply)\nSee [04_suppliers_and_companies §5](04_suppliers_and_companies.md) — manufacturer vs trader, legal name on FDA/CE docs, K-number coverage, label/IFU/UDI, OTC vs Rx, exact per-level output, single-vs-total energy, measuring lab, authorization letter.\n\n## Red flags\nSee [04_suppliers_and_companies §6](04_suppliers_and_companies.md) — \"FDA approved\" with no K-number; \"1450nm\" with no J/cm² or mJ/pulse; \"high energy\" with no pulse width/spot/profile; no contact sensor / no IEC 60825-1; home-use claims for melasma/mole/tattoo removal; \"fractional\" that's actually CO₂/IPL/RF/808nm hair removal.\n\n## Standards (why they're not random paperwork)\n- **IEC 60825-1** — laser product safety classification (180nm–1mm). Mandatory for any laser.\n- **IEC 60601-2-22** — medical/cosmetic laser equipment safety + performance.\n- **IEC 60601-1-11** — home-healthcare-environment requirements (relevant for OTC home devices).\n", "file": "06_sourcing_rfq_templates.md"}, {"id": "doc7", "md": "# Future Research Plan\n\nWhat to investigate next to confidently pick (or commission) an at-home device that gets closest to an efficacious in-office laser treatment for **pigment + long-term collagen**.\n\n**Guiding question:** *Of devices actually buyable today, which delivers the most of Clear + Brilliant's mechanism at home — and is it worth it vs a short in-office course + topicals?*\n\n---\n\n## Phase 0 — Decide the real strategy first (1 day, no spend)\nBefore any device research, settle the framing, because it changes everything downstream:\n- **Pigment is mostly a topicals + photoprotection problem**, not a device problem (parent repo [07](../01_ipl_hair_removal/07_alternatives_and_strategy.md)). Confirm you accept a home laser as an *adjunct/collagen tool*, not a pigment cure.\n- **Pick the primary goal:** if it's **pigment** → 1927nm path (Dora/Perméa class). If it's **collagen/texture** → 1450nm path (Tria/Iris class). If both → plan for *two* devices or an in-office Perméa course + home 1450nm maintenance.\n- **Set budget + risk tolerance:** trustworthy-FDA ($650 Tria) vs cheaper-China-verify-yourself ($420–600 YDUNVIE/MimiSilk) vs in-office course ($1,500–3,000).\n\n**Output:** one-paragraph decision recorded at top of the README.\n\n---\n\n## Phase 1 — Verify the top candidates against primary sources (1–2 weeks)\nTurn the ⚠️ marketing claims in [03](03_device_landscape.md) into ✅ or ❌. Priority order:\n\n| Candidate | What to verify | How |\n|-----------|----------------|-----|\n| **Tria FRX** | exact mJ/pulse, density, depth, real clinical data beyond periorbital | Read K130459 + K141868 PDFs fully; find independent reviews/studies |\n| **YDUNVIE Iris Ice / Plus** | true wavelength, mJ/pulse vs full-face J, density, cooling temp, K182498 coverage | Request datasheet from Jiangsu Unimed; pull K182498 PDF; compare Iris vs Iris Ice Plus in **same units** |\n| **YDUNVIE Dora (1927nm)** | confirm 1927nm, energy, depth, Fitzpatrick limits, PIH data | Datasheet + any clinical evidence; this is the pigment workhorse |\n| **MimiSilk Iris** | is it literally the YDUNVIE/Jiangsu Unimed device? what's its real K-number/UDI? | Ask MimiSilk for K-number + label; compare to K182498; check myernk \"authorized agent\" claim |\n\n**Key deliverable:** a one-page verified spec comparison (Tria vs Iris Ice Plus vs Dora vs Clear+Brilliant), all in identical units, single-pulse vs total clearly flagged.\n\n**Download for the repo:** the actual 510(k) PDFs (K130459, K141868, K163137, K222685, K090525, K133473, K182498, K231910, K244020) — mirror the parent repo's \"PDFs in repo\" practice.\n\n---\n\n## Phase 2 — Map the buyable market completely (1 week)\nFill gaps in [03](03_device_landscape.md). Devices/brands to chase down that the current pass only touched lightly:\n\n- **Discontinued-but-instructive:** PaloVia and Philips RéAura — find teardown reviews, manuals, real specs (they define \"home Fraxel done right\").\n- **Current China-market siblings:** OYAY (Iris/Dora), MimiSilk, myernk YDUNVIE, plus any other \"1450nm/1927nm at-home fractional\" brands (Iris Ice clones proliferate). Determine which are the **same Jiangsu Unimed hardware** vs distinct.\n- **Korean/other OEM:** the \"1450nm Accu Smart\"-type systems and any Korean home fractional devices.\n- **Newer in-office tech to benchmark against:** Sciton Moxi, LaseMD Ultra, Fraxel Dual — confirm their parameters as the \"efficacious ceiling.\"\n- **Adjacent (rule in/out):** confirm NIRA, LYMA, JOVS, DermRays are correctly categorized as *not* fractional resurfacers.\n\n**Deliverable:** expanded master table with a \"same-hardware-as?\" column and a verified ✅/⚠️ on every spec.\n\n---\n\n## Phase 3 — Clinical efficacy evidence review (1–2 weeks)\nThe current folder is strong on *specs* and weak on *outcomes*. Before buying, answer: **does the home version actually work, and how much?**\n\n- Find peer-reviewed trials for **home NAF lasers** (PaloVia multicenter trial is the anchor; search for Tria, RéAura studies).\n- Compare effect sizes: home NAF vs in-office Clear+Brilliant/Fraxel for (a) pigment/tone, (b) wrinkles/collagen.\n- Pull **realistic expectation numbers** (e.g., % improvement, sessions-to-result) to set expectations honestly.\n- Specifically search **1927nm at-home pigment** evidence and **PIH risk in Fitzpatrick III–VI** for these devices.\n\n**Deliverable:** a short evidence brief — \"what % of in-office results can a home fractional device realistically deliver, and over what timeframe.\"\n\n---\n\n## Phase 4 — Sourcing & verification execution (2–4 weeks)\nOperationalize [04](04_suppliers_and_companies.md) + [06](06_sourcing_rfq_templates.md):\n\n1. Send **RFQ #1 (1450nm)** and **RFQ #2 (1927nm)** to: Jiangsu Unimed/YDUNVIE (direct), Focuslight (OEM module), and 2–3 clinic suppliers (Gigaalaser, Liton) for context.\n2. Demand: K-number coverage, authorization letter, label/IFU/UDI, **calibrated output-measurement video**, single-vs-total energy clarification.\n3. Cross-check any \"FDA cleared\" claim against the actual K-number applicant.\n4. If buying a finished consumer unit: prefer an **authorized agent** with returns/warranty over a dropship store (OYAY-type).\n5. Negotiate China benchmark (~¥3,000–3,400 ≈ $417–$472 at ~¥7.2/$1 for YDUNVIE A9) vs Western relabel premiums.\n\n**Deliverable:** supplier scorecard (manufacturer-vs-trader, docs provided, real specs, price, MOQ, authorization) → a buy/no-buy recommendation.\n\n---\n\n## Phase 5 — Decision & protocol (a few days)\n- **Final pick** (or \"buy none — do in-office Perméa course + topicals\" if evidence says home isn't worth it).\n- **Usage/safety protocol** mirroring parent repo [06](../01_ipl_hair_removal/06_final_recommendation.md): cadence, ramp, cooling, SPF, contraindications, what to stop on.\n- If commissioning OEM: a spec contract derived from RFQ answers.\n\n---\n\n## Open questions to resolve (carried forward)\n1. Is **MimiSilk Iris == YDUNVIE Iris == Jiangsu Unimed K182498** the *same device*? (high-value: collapses 3 leads into 1)\n2. Does **Iris Ice Plus** have any real output advantage over Iris Ice, or only UX/cert? (current evidence: probably not)\n3. Is there a **buyable home 1927nm** device with credible PIH-safety data, or is in-office Perméa/Moxi the only safe pigment route?\n4. What is the **real per-session and cumulative efficacy** of home NAF vs Clear+Brilliant? (Phase 3)\n5. **Discontinued PaloVia/RéAura** — any new-old-stock or refurbished units worth acquiring to study/use?\n6. **Eye safety** of cheap China home lasers near the periorbital area — independently verified or just claimed?\n\n---\n\n## How to run this efficiently\n- This whole plan is a good fit for the repo's **deep-research** approach (multi-source, adversarially verified, cited) — e.g. invoke `/deep-research` per phase with the phase's guiding question.\n- Mirror parent-repo discipline: **download primary PDFs into the repo**, label every claim ✅/⚠️/🔍, and force all specs into identical units before comparing.\n- Keep the README TL;DR updated as each phase resolves ⚠️ → ✅/❌.\n", "file": "07_future_research_plan.md"}, {"id": "doc8", "md": "# The Quantified Gap: Clear + Brilliant vs Home Lasers (Dermatology Evidence)\n\n**Your hypothesis:** *\"It's the density, since the pulse energy seems similar.\"* This document tests that against the published parameters. **Verdict up front: you're ~70% right.** Per-pulse energy is genuinely similar — so energy is *not* the differentiator. But the gap is **three stacked factors, not one**: (1) **coverage density per session**, (2) **depth / optical quality of each microcolumn**, and (3) **uniformity + supervised cumulative dosing**. Density is the most quantifiable single factor and a real gap, but **depth is the silent co-driver** that pure energy numbers hide.\n\nConfidence: ✅ verified (peer-reviewed / FDA) · ⚠️ marketing/company study · 🔍 inferred.\n\n---\n\n## 1. The four parameters that actually define a fractional treatment\n\nA non-ablative fractional laser (NAFL) result is governed by four independent levers — and marketing usually quotes only the first:\n\n| Lever | Definition | Who controls it |\n|-------|-----------|-----------------|\n| **1. Pulse energy** (mJ/microbeam) | energy in a single microcolumn → intensity | fixed presets (home) / provider (clinic) — **home ≈ clinic** |\n| **2. Density / coverage** (MTZ/cm² or % surface treated) | how much skin is injured per session | passes × setting; **provider goes far higher → THE gap** (§3) |\n| **3. Depth** (µm) | how deep each microcolumn reaches → dermal vs epidermal | **WAVELENGTH** (water absorption); energy nudges it within that window — **home ≈ clinic at matched λ** (§4) |\n| **4. Dose control** (uniformity, passes, sessions, tuning to an endpoint) | total + even remodeling stimulus over a course | provider scanner + course (clinic) ≫ open-ended manual self-use (home) — **the other gap** (§5) |\n\n*(Levers 1 & 3 are roughly equal home-vs-clinic; the gap lives in 2 & 4.)*\n\nThe key conceptual identity from the fractional-laser literature:\n\n> **Coverage % ≈ MTZ density (per cm²) × microbeam cross-sectional area.**\n> Example (✅ from the literature): a *10 mJ @ 2,000 MTZ/cm²* treatment and a *20 mJ @ 1,000 MTZ/cm²* treatment **both = 20% coverage** — same coverage, different energy/depth. Energy and density are *separable*, which is exactly why \"12 mJ!\" tells you almost nothing on its own.\n\nFractional lasers by definition treat only **5–50% of the skin surface** per session, leaving untreated bridges to heal from. ✅\n\n---\n\n## 2. Lever 1 — Pulse energy: home ≈ in-office (your intuition is correct ✅)\n\n| Device | Class | Wavelength | Per-microbeam energy | Source |\n|--------|-------|-----------|----------------------|--------|\n| **Clear + Brilliant Original** | in-office | 1440nm | **4 / 7 / 9 mJ** (3 levels) | ✅ FDA 9mJ max; fractional lit. |\n| **Clear + Brilliant Perméa** | in-office | 1927nm | **5 mJ** max | ✅ FDA |\n| **Fraxel re:store** | in-office (stronger) | 1550nm | 6–25 mJ | ✅ skintherapyletter |\n| **Tria FRX / Age-Defying** | **home** | 1440nm | **5 / 10 / 12 mJ** (3 levels) | ⚠️ 15MinuteBeauty/company |\n| **PaloVia** | **home** | 1410nm | ~10–15 mJ | ⚠️ |\n| **MimiSilk / YDUNVIE Iris** | **home** | 1450nm | up to 12 mJ | ⚠️ seller |\n\n**Finding:** home fractional devices fire microbeams at **5–12 mJ** — *the same as, or higher than,* Clear + Brilliant's **4–9 mJ**. Tria's own marketing (\"the same technology available in a doctor's office\") is, *on the energy axis alone,* roughly defensible. **So energy is not where the gap lives.** ✅ Your premise holds.\n\n> ⚠️ Caveat: equal *surface* mJ ≠ equal *delivered* effect, because depth depends on optics (Lever 3). Two devices can both say \"12 mJ\" and put very different amounts of heat at 300 µm.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Lever 2 — Density / coverage: the gap you predicted (partly ✅)\n\n### Clear + Brilliant (✅ fractional-laser literature)\n- 1440nm handpiece: three settings **low / medium / high → 5% / 7.5% / 10% coverage** *when 8 passes are made* over the area.\n- So even at \"high,\" C+B treats ~**10% of the surface per session** — and notably, C+B is described as **\"the less intense\"** member of the NAFL family.\n\n### Fraxel re:store (✅ skintherapyletter) — the stronger in-office benchmark\n- Coverage **5–29%**; MTZ density **750–3,000 / cm²**; per-pass ~**250 MTZ/cm²**, building to a final **1,500–2,500 MTZ/cm²** with multiple passes.\n\n### Home devices — the transparency gap 🔍\n- **Tria, PaloVia, YDUNVIE/MimiSilk do not publish MTZ/cm² or coverage %.** They disclose energy levels and treatment *time/cadence*, never density. That silence is itself informative: home devices are engineered for **low per-session coverage** so unsupervised daily use stays safe.\n- Tria's mechanism description is qualitative only: *\"as you go up in levels… the laser will create more MTZs.\"* ⚠️ — i.e. density is adjustable but unquantified.\n\n**Finding:** density/coverage is the **real, dominant gap.** C+B's own coverage (5–10%) isn't enormous — it's *lower* than Fraxel — but it's still **~10–30× the home per-session density** (quantified in §3b). The home gap is **\"home devices deliver lower, uneven, undisclosed density per session, and you can't dial it to a clinical endpoint.\"** (Depth is *not* the next missing piece — §4 shows it's wavelength-set and ≈ equal at matched λ; the other half of the gap is **dose control**, not depth.)\n\n---\n\n## 3b. Estimating the home MTZ density from \"180 J full-face\" 🔍 (the calculation you asked for)\n\nHome sellers hide density — but the **total-energy figure leaks it.** If you know total energy per session, energy per microbeam, and the treated area, density falls out. This is back-of-envelope (±2×), but it's anchored and it **cross-checks against two independent specs**, so the order of magnitude is trustworthy.\n\n### Inputs (from YDUNVIE Iris Ice / A9, A7 Iris, MimiSilk Iris — they share a spec fingerprint)\n> *Reading \"M7/M9\" as the YDUNVIE **A7** (Iris) / **A9** (Iris Ice); these + MimiSilk Iris all report ~12 mJ max, ~100 µm microbeam, 1450nm — so one calculation covers the family.*\n\n| Symbol | Value | Source |\n|--------|-------|--------|\n| **E_total** (energy/session) | **180 J** full-face | ⚠️ YDUNVIE Iris Ice spec |\n| **e_MTZ** (energy/microbeam) | **3–12 mJ** (central **8 mJ**) | ⚠️ MimiSilk \"12 mJ max\"; Iris Ice Plus \"3–12 mJ\" |\n| **d** (microbeam diameter) | **~100 µm** → area a = π/4·d² = **7.85×10⁻⁵ cm²** | ⚠️ MimiSilk \"100 µm microbeam\" |\n| **A_face** (treated area) | **~400 cm²** (range 350–450) | 🔍 standard full-face estimate |\n\n### The formulas\n```\nMTZs per session   N   = E_total / e_MTZ\nMTZ density        ρ   = N / A_face\nCoverage %         C   = ρ × a_MTZ\nArea-avg fluence   F   = E_total / A_face\nLocal MTZ fluence  F_L = e_MTZ / a_MTZ\n```\n\n### Worked central case (8 mJ, 100 µm, 400 cm²)\n- **N = 180 / 0.008 = 22,500 microbeams/session**\n- **ρ = 22,500 / 400 ≈ 56 MTZ/cm²**\n- **C = 56 × 7.85×10⁻⁵ ≈ 0.44% coverage/session**\n- **F = 180 / 400 ≈ 0.45 J/cm²** (area-averaged)\n- F_L = 0.008 / 7.85×10⁻⁵ ≈ **102 J/cm²** within each column (high, as expected)\n\n### Two independent cross-checks (this is why I trust the ~order of magnitude)\n1. **Firing rate:** 22,500 MTZ ÷ ~600 s (10-min full face) = **~38 MTZ/s** — almost exactly the **\"36 light spots/second\"** the Iluminage listing quotes. ✅ independent agreement.\n2. **MimiSilk's \"~2.11 J/cm²\":** my per-session area-avg is ~0.45 J/cm². Across the ~4–5 passes these devices recommend, 0.45 × ~4.7 ≈ **2.1 J/cm²** — matches MimiSilk's stated figure. ✅ So \"2.11 J/cm²\" is cumulative-per-session, and my coverage estimate reconciles.\n\n### Sensitivity (density & coverage scale inversely with per-beam energy)\n| e_MTZ | MTZs/session | **Density (MTZ/cm²)** | **Coverage** |\n|-------|--------------|----------------------|--------------|\n| 3 mJ | 60,000 | **~150** | ~1.2% |\n| 8 mJ (central) | 22,500 | **~56** | ~0.44% |\n| 12 mJ | 15,000 | **~38** | ~0.3% |\n\n→ **Home per-session density ≈ 40–150 MTZ/cm²; coverage ≈ 0.3–1.2%.**\n\n### Tria FRX — better disclosure, same ballpark (with one real advantage) 🔍\nTria gives us more to work with than YDUNVIE/MimiSilk: it **discloses a coverage fraction directly**, plus depth.\n\n| Symbol | Value | Source |\n|--------|-------|--------|\n| Wavelength | 1440nm | ✅ |\n| e_MTZ | 5 / 10 / 12 mJ (by level) | ⚠️ reviews/IFU |\n| **Coverage fraction** | **0.25%–5% per treatment** | ⚠️ Tria patent \"home-use embodiment\" — *disclosed design envelope* |\n| **Depth** | ~450 µm quoted (but = wavelength-set; **same as any 1440nm device incl. C+B** — not an advantage, see §4) | ⚠️ Tria |\n| Treatment | 2–10 min/session, 5×/week × 12 wk, then 4 wk off; full face | ✅ Tria |\n| MTZ diameter (assumed) | ~100–150 µm | 🔍 NAFL class |\n\n**Density from coverage** (ρ = coverage ÷ MTZ area):\n- At the **disclosed envelope** (0.25–5%, 100–150 µm spot): ρ ≈ **14–640 MTZ/cm²** — a very wide band because 0.25–5% is a *design* range, not the FRX's actual per-session number.\n- **Power/energy reality check:** a handheld with ~45 min total battery per charge can't deliver the high end. If per-session energy is ~180–360 J (same class as YDUNVIE) at 5–12 mJ, that's **~30–180 MTZ/cm², ~0.3–1.5% coverage** — i.e. the **low end** of Tria's own envelope, essentially matching the Iris/MimiSilk estimate (same device class, same power budget).\n\n**On the \"450 µm depth\" — not actually an advantage (corrected).** Tria and C+B Original are **both 1440nm**, so their depth is fundamentally the same (wavelength sets it — see §4). Tria's quoted \"~450 µm\" vs C+B's \"~300–400 µm\" is within-window noise from differently-measured numbers, *not* a real edge. So Tria is **not** deeper in any meaningful sense — it sits in the **same low density band as Iris/MimiSilk (~30–180 MTZ/cm²) at the same 1440nm depth.** Its only genuine distinctions are non-physics: **FDA clearance + a real company** (see [03](03_device_landscape.md)). (And at 1440nm it's a collagen/texture tool — its labeling is cautious on dyschromia — so it's off-target for *your pigment* goal regardless.)\n\n### Head-to-head with the benchmarks\n| Device | Density/session | Coverage/session | Area-avg fluence | Depth |\n|--------|----------------|------------------|------------------|-------|\n| **Home Iris / MimiSilk (estimated 🔍)** | **~40–150 MTZ/cm²** | **~0.3–1.2%** | ~0.45 J/cm² (≈2.1 cumulative) | shallow |\n| **Tria FRX (estimated 🔍)** | **~30–180 MTZ/cm²** (power-feasible); 14–640 disclosed envelope | **~0.3–1.5%** likely (0.25–5% disclosed) | ~0.5–1 J/cm² | ~300–450 µm (1440nm — same as C+B) |\n| **Clear + Brilliant (high)** | **~650–1,270 MTZ/cm²** ✅ | **10%** (8 passes) | ~11 J/cm² | ~300–400 µm (1440nm) |\n| **Fraxel re:store** | **750–3,000 MTZ/cm²** ✅ | 5–29% | higher | 250–800 µm (1550nm) |\n\n> **The number you wanted:** per session, both the home Iris/MimiSilk **and the Tria FRX** deliver roughly **1/10th to 1/30th the MTZ density and ~20× less coverage than Clear + Brilliant on high** — *quantifying* the \"it's the density\" hypothesis. All three 1440/1450nm devices sit at the **same wavelength-set depth**, so depth doesn't separate them; **the gap is density/coverage, full stop.** (C+B density derived from its 10% coverage ÷ ~100–140 µm MTZ area; depth column shown by wavelength to make clear it's *not* the differentiator within 1440nm.)\n\n### The cumulative caveat (this is the home device's one real argument)\nHome devices are used **far more often**. At 2–3×/week for ~12 weeks (~30 sessions):\n- Home cumulative ≈ 30 × 56 ≈ **~1,700 MTZ/cm²**\n- A C+B course (4–6 sessions) ≈ **~2,600–7,600 MTZ/cm²**\n\nSo with religious months-long consistency, home *cumulative* density climbs to within ~2–4× of a C+B course — **but** each session's stimulus is too **sparse** (low density) to drive confluent remodeling the way a denser session does, and skin **fully regenerates between sessions** so the injuries don't truly \"bank.\" **Frequency partially compensates for density, but many sparse healing events ≠ one dense one** — that's the limit, *not* depth (which is wavelength-set and ≈ equal at matched λ; see §4).\n\n---\n\n## 3c. Does staggering low-density sessions match one high-density Clear + Brilliant? — the research\n\nYou asked the right question. There **is** published research on *exactly* this trade-off — \"low-density / more-sessions\" vs \"high-density / fewer-sessions.\" **The answer flips depending on your goal**, and for *your* goal (pigment) it's genuinely encouraging — with one big home-device asterisk.\n\n> First, a framing note: **a single \"one-time\" Clear + Brilliant is itself a slightly false baseline** — C+B is normally done as a **series of 4–6**. The real question the literature answers is *high-density-fewer-sessions* vs *low-density-more-sessions* at matched total dose.\n\n### For PIGMENT / melasma / PIH (your goal): staggered low-density isn't just \"as good\" — it's *preferred* ✅\n- ✅ **Density, not energy, is the dominant driver of PIH.** [Chan et al. 2010, *Lasers Surg Med* (PubMed 21246574)](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/21246574/) found that in Asian skin **density — more than pulse energy — was associated with PIH**; an [Alexis et al. split-face study](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC5605208/) holding fluence constant at 40 mJ while varying density (220 vs 393 MTZ/cm²) found satisfaction rose with *fluence*, not density — while higher density mainly raised PIH. So for pigment-prone skin, **lower density per session is safer at equal efficacy.**\n- ✅ **\"Mini\" (low-density, more sessions) = \"full\" (high-density, fewer) on efficacy, with *less* PIH.** [Chan et al. (PubMed 21246574)](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/21246574/) compared **full-NAFR (3 sessions × 8 passes) vs mini-NAFR (6 sessions × 4 passes)** in Asian acne-scar patients: **no difference in efficacy, but statistically lower PIH** in the mini (low-density) arm. Summarized in the [JCAD *Nonablative Fractional Resurfacing in Skin of Color* review (PMC5605208)](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC5605208/).\n- ✅ **Low-energy, low-density 1927nm works for melasma/PIH/photodamage.** [Brauer, Alabdulrazzaq, Bae & Geronemus 2015, *JDD* (PubMed 26580875)](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26580875/): 23 subjects, **5 mJ, 5/7.5/10% density, 4–6 sessions at 14-day intervals → ~55% marked-to-very-significant improvement, maintained at 3 months.** Reinforced by [Bae et al. 2020 low-energy 1927nm for PIH in darker skin (PubMed 31663147)](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31663147/). The gentle-repeated model is the *standard of care* for pigment, not a compromise.\n- ⚠️ **A single aggressive (high-coverage) session can be actively *worse* for melasma.** The [Indian Pigmentary Expert Group melasma consensus (PMC5724305)](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC5724305/) documents high recurrence/PIH risk when fractional settings are too aggressive in melasma. (The specific \"≥12% coverage → 340% rebound / ultra-low 80–120 MTZ/cm² + TXA\" figures come from a [manufacturer FAQ](https://www.cocoonlaser.com/fractional-photothermolysis-density-coverage-percentage-explained-clinic-investment-faq/) — ⚠️ directional only, but consistent with the peer-reviewed \"density drives PIH/rebound\" theme.)\n\n**→ For pigment, the home \"frequent low-density\" paradigm is on the *right* side of the evidence. A single big high-density C+B session wouldn't even be the goal — derms deliberately go low-and-slow for pigment.**\n\n### For COLLAGEN / texture / scars: high-density per session generally wins ⚠️\n- ✅ **Hypertrophic burn-scar RCT (3 sessions each):** [*High- Versus Low-Density Fractional Laser in the Treatment of Hypertrophic Postburn Scars: A Randomized Clinical Trial* (PubMed 31851017)](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31851017/) — high-density significantly **out-performed** low-density on VSS/POSAS **and** histology (p<0.001). For deep dermal remodeling, density matters and low-density loses.\n- ✅ **Acne-scar split-face (CO₂):** [*Lower-Fluence, Higher-Density vs Higher-Fluence, Lower-Density 10,600-nm CO₂ fractional, split-face, evaluator-blinded* (PubMed 21070459)](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/21070459/) — the **higher-fluence/lower-density** arm produced more \"marked\" (>76%) improvement. Per-session intensity (energy/depth per column), not raw density, drove scar results here.\n- ✅ **Collagen remodeling is cumulative over months** — [fractional resurfacing drives delayed neocollagenesis (PMC7028380)](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC7028380/), so stacking sessions does add up for wrinkles — *but* the comparative data above says low-density needs **more** sessions to *approach* (not always equal) high-density, and may underperform for deep work.\n\n**→ For collagen/scars, staggering low-density can *approach* a denser protocol only with enough sessions, and is sometimes inferior — the opposite of the pigment story.**\n\n### The math that limits \"just do more sessions\": coverage is NOT additive\nCumulative coverage across *n* sessions follows **C_cum = 1 − (1 − C)ⁿ** (spots heal and overlap between sessions). Applying it to the home device (per-session C ≈ 0.44%, from §3b):\n\n| Home sessions | Cumulative surface coverage |\n|---------------|-----------------------------|\n| 10 | ~4.3% |\n| **~24** | **~10% — i.e. *one* C+B-high session's coverage** |\n| 30 | ~12.4% |\n| **~144** | **~47% — i.e. a *6-session* C+B course's cumulative coverage** |\n\nSo matching **one** high-density C+B session takes **~24 home sessions**; matching a **full C+B course** takes **~140+** (≈1–1.4 years at 2–3×/week). And three caveats blunt even that:\n1. **Coverage ≠ remodeling.** Many sparse healing events ≠ one dense healing event — a denser single wound-healing response drives stronger dermal remodeling (why high-density wins for scars).\n2. **Skin fully regenerates between sessions**, so home injuries don't \"bank\" the way the formula's spatial coverage implies — especially for collagen.\n3. **Manual coverage is uneven** — handheld gliding leaves gaps and overlaps, so real cumulative coverage is lower and patchier than the idealized formula assumes (vs C+B's optical scanner). *(Note: depth is NOT a caveat here — at matched wavelength home reaches the same depth as C+B; see §4.)*\n\n### Bottom line for your situation\n- **Pigment (your priority):** ✅ **staggered low-density is the evidence-based approach, not a downgrade** — and it's *safer* for PIH-prone skin than one aggressive session. The home cadence matches best practice *in principle*. The asterisk: the research is on **clinical** devices with **disclosed** density; a home device's density is unverified (probably sub-therapeutic). Depth isn't the issue for pigment anyway — you'd *want* a shallow 1927nm device. So this is the category where home is **closest** to legitimate.\n- **Collagen/texture:** ⚠️ staggering **does not reliably substitute** for clinical *density*; you'd need many sessions to approach it and may still fall short, because sparse per-session coverage drives weaker remodeling than a denser one.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Lever 3 — Depth: set by WAVELENGTH, not by home-vs-clinic (corrected)\n\n> **Correction (you were right to push on this).** An earlier draft treated depth as a home-vs-clinic \"gap.\" That's wrong at matched wavelength. **Depth is dominated by wavelength**, via water absorption — so comparing a 1440nm home device's quoted depth to a 1440nm C+B's quoted depth tells you almost nothing. Depth is a lever you pull by **choosing the wavelength**, *not* a place where clinic beats home.\n\n**Wavelength sets the depth scale** (1/e optical penetration ≈ 1/water-absorption-coefficient):\n\n| Wavelength | Water absorption | Optical penetration / typical MTZ depth | Source |\n|-----------|------------------|------------------------------------------|--------|\n| **1440–1450nm** (C+B Original, **Tria**, Iris, NIRA) | moderate (~30 cm⁻¹) | **~300–450 µm** | ✅ JDD NAF review; absorption physics |\n| **1550nm** (Fraxel re:store) | higher | 250–800 µm (energy-dependent) | ✅ skintherapyletter |\n| **1927nm** (C+B Perméa, Moxi, Dora) | very high (~10–20×) | **~170 µm** | ✅ JDD NAF review |\n\n**The two things that are TRUE about depth:**\n1. **Across wavelengths it's decisive** — 1927nm (~170 µm, pigment) vs 1450nm (~300–450 µm, collagen) is a real, physics-locked difference. *This* is the depth lever that matters, and it's the basis of the whole pigment-vs-collagen split in [09](09_1927nm_vs_1450nm_headtohead.md).\n2. **Within a wavelength, energy modulates MTZ depth modestly** — more mJ pushes the damage isotherm toward the deeper end of the wavelength's window. But Tria's 5–12 mJ overlaps C+B's 4–9 mJ, so **at matched wavelength + energy, Tria and C+B Original reach essentially the same depth.** The \"Tria ~450 µm vs C+B ~300–400 µm\" comparison is within-window noise from differently-defined/marketed numbers — **not a real Tria advantage.** (Correction applied in §3b too.)\n\n**So depth is NOT a separate home-vs-clinic lever.** At matched wavelength it collapses into wavelength (fixed) + energy (similar). The honest residual caveat: beam *quality/focusing* and *uniformity* can shape the column somewhat, but that's secondary and unproven — not the order-of-magnitude story that **density/coverage** (Lever 2) is.\n\n**This actually strengthens your original \"it's the density\" instinct:** with energy ≈ matched and depth ≈ wavelength-locked, the dominant home-vs-clinic gap is **density/coverage + dose control (uniformity, passes, sessions, provider tuning)** — full stop.\n\n---\n\n## 4b. Microbeam diameter — the spec nobody quotes (and what it actually changes)\n\nGood instinct to ask. Microbeam **diameter** is a real, separate variable — and it interacts with everything above. Two diameters matter: the **incidence spot** (beam width at the skin surface) and the resulting **MTZ diameter** (the thermal-damage column, usually a bit wider than the incidence spot as heat spreads).\n\n**Typical values (✅ literature):**\n| Device | Microbeam / MTZ diameter |\n|--------|--------------------------|\n| Manstein original fractional concept | ~**60 µm or 140 µm** incidence (Gaussian) |\n| **Clear + Brilliant** | **fixed ~140 µm**; Perméa 110–180 µm |\n| **Fraxel re:store** | MTZ ~**100 µm** dia (e.g. 20 mJ/60 µm spot → 100 µm × 300 µm deep) |\n| Home (MimiSilk Iris) | ~**100 µm** (stated) |\n| General MTZ range | **~50–200 µm**, grows with skin temperature (93→147 µm as 0→45 °C) |\n\n**Why diameter matters — four real effects:**\n\n1. **It sets fluence at a fixed energy (the big one).** Fluence = energy ÷ beam area, and area scales with **diameter²** — so a *smaller* beam concentrates the *same mJ* into a *much higher* J/cm², making a **deeper, more intense** column. The counterintuitive consequence for your devices:\n   - Home (MimiSilk) **12 mJ / 100 µm → ~150 J/cm²** per column\n   - C+B Original **9 mJ / 140 µm → ~58 J/cm²** per column\n   So **per-column, a small-spot home device can be *more* intense than C+B**, not less. (Even 5 mJ/100 µm ≈ 64 J/cm² ≈ C+B.) Per-column intensity is **not** where home loses.\n2. **It drives the coverage math (diameter²).** A 140 µm beam covers ~2× the skin area of a 100 µm beam at the same density — which is exactly why the §3b density estimate is diameter-sensitive (I used ~100 µm for home, ~100–140 µm for C+B). Smaller spots need *higher density* to reach the same coverage.\n3. **Smaller = faster, safer healing.** Tiny columns surrounded by intact tissue re-epithelialize **<24 h** with minimal side effects — the whole safety premise of \"fractional.\" Larger MTZs remodel more per column but heal slower and carry more PIH risk.\n4. **Focus stability — the genuine home-vs-clinic catch.** Fluence depends on the beam staying in focus. **Handpiece pressure/movement shifts the focal plane, *enlarges* the effective spot, and *drops* fluence → shallower, weaker lesions and compromised efficacy** (✅ documented). A clinic **optical scanner holds the focal plane**; a hand-glided home device depends on *your* consistent contact — so home risks an **uncontrolled, drifting diameter** that under-doses in practice. (Cooling helps too: MTZ diameter grows with skin temperature, so contact/\"ice\" cooling keeps the column tight and predictable.)\n\n**Verdict on diameter:** per-column, home diameter/fluence/intensity **match or exceed** C+B — so diameter is *not* a deficiency in the home device's favor-of-clinic column (if anything a small hot spot raises **PIH risk**, another reason for cooling + conservative settings). The diameter-related issue that *does* hurt home efficacy is **inconsistency** — defocus/drift from manual use — which belongs to the **dose-control / uniformity** lever (§5), not a per-spec disadvantage. Bottom line unchanged: **the gap is density + dose control, not energy, depth, or beam diameter.**\n\n---\n\n## 5. Lever 4 — Cumulative, supervised dosing\n\n| | Clear + Brilliant | Home NAFL |\n|---|-------------------|-----------|\n| **Per-session aggression** | provider escalates; **topical numbing** lets the patient tolerate higher energy/density | capped low so it's painless/safe unsupervised; pain self-limits dose |\n| **Coverage placement** | **optical scanner** → uniform, full-area, reproducible | manual glide → uneven, gaps/overlaps, contact-dependent |\n| **Wavelengths** | **two** (1440 *and* 1927) — collagen *and* pigment in one platform | usually **one** per device |\n| **Course** | ~**4–6 sessions** to a clinical endpoint + maintenance | **open-ended self-treatment** over months; no endpoint control |\n| **Tuning** | per-pass, per-skin-response | fixed presets |\n\nNumbing is an underrated multiplier: because a provider can anesthetize, the *tolerable* per-session dose in-office is higher than anything a home user will sit through, compounding the density gap.\n\n---\n\n## 6. Clinical outcomes — what the numbers translate to\n\nDirect head-to-head RCTs (home vs C+B) don't exist, so compare the published outcomes with caution:\n\n| Device | Study type | Headline result | Read |\n|--------|-----------|-----------------|------|\n| **PaloVia** (home, 1410nm) | ✅ peer-reviewed multicenter (JAAD 2012) | **90%** improved ≥1 Fitzpatrick wrinkle grade at end of *daily* active phase; **79%** at end of twice-weekly maintenance | real but **modest absolute** change (≥1 grade), requiring daily use for weeks |\n| **Tria Age-Defying** (home, 1440nm) | ⚠️ company study | 76% improved periorbital at 4 wks; \"93% smoother / 82% periorbital\" | vendor data; \"improvement\" loosely defined |\n| **Clear + Brilliant** (in-office) | clinical use + studies | texture/tone/pigment improvement, enhanced topical penetration; collagen builds over months | deeper remodeling in **far fewer sessions**; provider-controlled |\n\n**Interpretation:** home devices *do* produce measurable improvement — but the endpoints are lenient (≥1 grade on a wrinkle scale), achieved through **daily/weekly use over months**. C+B reaches the same result in ~4–6 supervised sessions by delivering far higher density per session. The home result is a *real fraction* of the in-office result, not zero — consistent with \"same energy, same (wavelength-set) depth, **much less density + cumulative dose control.**\"\n\n---\n\n## 7. The honest, quantified verdict\n\n```\nPulse energy:     home (5–12 mJ)  ≈  Clear+Brilliant (4–9 mJ)          → NOT the gap ✅\nDepth:            home & C+B at 1440nm both ~300–450 µm (WAVELENGTH-set)  → NOT a home-vs-clinic gap ✅\n                  (depth is a lever you pull by CHOOSING λ: 1927nm≈170µm pigment vs 1450nm≈350µm collagen)\nBeam diameter:    home ~100µm/12mJ ≈ 150 J/cm²  ≥  C+B 140µm/9mJ ≈ 58 J/cm² → per-column NOT the gap ✅\n                  (small spot = higher fluence; home's diameter RISK is drift/defocus → dose-control, §4b)\nCoverage/density: home (~30–180 MTZ/cm², ~0.3–1.5%/session, est.)\n                     vs  C+B high (~650–1,270 MTZ/cm², 10%)  ≈ 10–30× lower → THE gap (quantified §3b)\nCumulative dose:  home (open-ended, painless, single-λ, manual)\n                     < C+B (4–6 sessions, numbed, dual-λ, scanned, to endpoint) → the other gap\n```\n\n- **You're right that it's not energy — and (correction) it's not depth either.** At matched wavelength, depth is wavelength-locked and home ≈ clinic; depth only matters as a *wavelength-choice* lever (1927 vs 1450). ✅\n- **So it really is mostly density.** The dominant home-vs-clinic gap is **coverage/density per session** (~10–30× lower), plus **dose control** (uniformity, passes, sessions, provider tuning to an endpoint). Your original instinct holds up better than my earlier \"density + depth\" framing.\n- **Net effect:** a home NAFL delivers maybe a *modest fraction* of a C+B session's remodeling stimulus (low density), so it needs **many more sessions** and **plateaus lower**, but it is the **same mechanism** at the **same wavelength/depth** and produces **real, measurable** change.\n\n---\n\n## 8. What this means for your buying decision\n\n1. **Don't pay for \"higher energy\" *or* \"deeper\" home claims.** 12 mJ already matches C+B, and depth is fixed by wavelength (all the 1440/1450nm devices are equal) — so neither is a differentiator. The spec that actually matters — **MTZ density/cm² (or coverage %)** — is the one home sellers won't give you. **Demand it** ([06 RFQ](06_sourcing_rfq_templates.md)).\n2. **A home NAFL is a legitimate *maintenance/cumulative* tool, not a C+B replacement.** Best ROI: a short **in-office C+B course** (esp. **Perméa 1927nm** for your pigment goal) to do the deep work, then a home 1450nm device to maintain — you're buying the home device for *frequency*, not *depth*.\n3. **For pigment specifically,** depth matters *less* (pigment is superficial), so the home-vs-clinic gap is **smallest for a 1927nm device** (YDUNVIE Dora / clinic Perméa). That's the one category where a home device is closest to efficacious — *if* its 1927nm + cooling are verified. (Pair with topicals + SPF regardless — parent [07](../01_ipl_hair_removal/07_alternatives_and_strategy.md).)\n4. **The questions that decide value** for any home unit: *what's the wavelength (which sets depth + target), and what's the per-session coverage / MTZ density?* Wavelength tells you *what* it treats; density tells you *how far below C+B* it is. Depth follows from wavelength, so it's not a separate question.\n\n---\n\n### Sources\n- [Skin Therapy Letter — Fractional Laser Treatment for Pigmentation & Texture](https://www.skintherapyletter.com/hyperpigmentation/fractional-laser-treatment/) (Fraxel density 750–3,000 MTZ/cm², coverage 5–29%, depth 250–800 µm; C+B coverage levels)\n- [JDD — The 1440nm & 1927nm Nonablative Fractional Diode Laser review](https://jddonline.com/articles/article-the-1440-nm-and-1927-nm-nonablative-fractional-diode-laser-current-trends-and-future-directi-S1545961620S00s3X/) (C+B depths, energy levels)\n- [PaloVia multicenter home NAFL trial — JAAD 2012 (PubMed 22386051)](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22386051/) (90%/79% Fitzpatrick improvement)\n- [Tria Age-Defying / FRX review (energy levels 5/10/12 mJ; 450 µm depth)](https://www.15minutebeauty.com/tria-age-defying-laser-review.html) · [Tria FRX product page (2–10 min, 5×/wk × 12 wk)](https://www.trialaser.com/products/frx-fractional-skin-rejuvenating-laser) · [Tria patent — \"home-use embodiment\" coverage 0.25–5% (US 9308390 et al.)](https://image-ppubs.uspto.gov/dirsearch-public/print/downloadPdf/9308390) ⚠️\n- [Clear + Brilliant vs Fraxel Dual (Art of Dermatology)](https://artofdermatology.com/anti-aging-laser-treatments-clear-and-brilliant-vs-fraxel-dual-restore/) · [Greenwich Dermatology — Fraxel science](https://www.greenwichdermatology.com/blog/fraxel-restore-laser-science/)\n- [Clear + Brilliant Touch FDA specs (NCT05027282 protocol)](https://clinicaltrials.gov/study/NCT05027282)\n- **§4b (microbeam diameter):** [Manstein — Fractional Photothermolysis foundational paper (60/140 µm microbeams)](https://www.researchgate.net/publication/8490799_Fractional_Photothermolysis_A_New_Concept_for_Cutaneous_Remodeling_Using_Microscopic_Patterns_of_Thermal_Injury) · [Focal-point technology — spot size, focus drift & lesion depth (JAAD 2024)](https://www.jaad.org/article/S0190-9622(24)02809-3/fulltext) · [Skin temperature ↑ → MTZ diameter ↑ 93→147 µm (PubMed 17252573)](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/17252573/) · [Imaging 1927nm thulium tissue interactions — nonablative→ablative (PMC12264580)](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC12264580/) · re-epithelialization <24 h with small MTZs (Skin Therapy Letter)\n- **§3c (staggered vs high-density) — primary studies:**\n  - [Chan et al. 2010 — full-NAFR vs mini-NAFR in Asian acne scars; density > energy for PIH (PubMed 21246574)](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/21246574/) *(the mini-vs-full study)*\n  - [Brauer, Alabdulrazzaq, Bae & Geronemus 2015 — low-energy/low-density 1927nm for photodamage/melasma/PIH, *JDD* (PubMed 26580875)](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26580875/)\n  - [Bae et al. 2020 — low-energy 1927nm NAFL for PIH in darker skin (PubMed 31663147)](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31663147/)\n  - [High- vs Low-Density fractional for hypertrophic postburn scars — RCT, high-density wins (PubMed 31851017)](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31851017/)\n  - [Lower-fluence/higher-density vs higher-fluence/lower-density CO₂ fractional, split-face, evaluator-blinded (PubMed 21070459)](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/21070459/)\n  - [Nonablative Fractional Resurfacing in Skin of Color — evidence review (PMC5605208)](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC5605208/) · [Lasers in Melasma — Indian Pigmentary Expert consensus (PMC5724305)](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC5724305/) · [Fractional resurfacing neocollagenesis over months (PMC7028380)](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC7028380/) · [cumulative-coverage formula explainer (Cocoon, ⚠️ manufacturer)](https://www.cocoonlaser.com/fractional-photothermolysis-density-coverage-percentage-explained-clinic-investment-faq/)\n", "file": "08_clear_brilliant_quantified_gap.md"}, {"id": "doc9", "md": "# 1927nm vs 1450nm: Head-to-Head for *Your* Profile (25, pigment-focused)\n\n**The framing correction you need first:** \"1450nm is more research-backed\" is **true — but for the wrong problem.** 1450nm has excellent evidence for **acne, acne scars, fine wrinkles, and collagen**. It is **not a pigment treatment** — it targets water/collagen/sebaceous glands and barely touches brown pigment. For **your stated #1 concern (pigmentation), 1927nm is decisively more research-backed.** So this isn't \"pigment device vs the better-studied device\" — it's \"the pigment wavelength vs the collagen/acne wavelength,\" and they treat different things.\n\nConfidence: ✅ peer-reviewed · ⚠️ marketing/weak · 🔍 inferred.\n\n---\n\n## 1. The two wavelengths at a glance\n\n| | **1927nm** (thulium/diode) | **1450nm** (diode) |\n|---|---------------------------|--------------------|\n| **Water absorption** | **very high** (~10–20× the 1550nm class) | moderate |\n| **Depth** | **superficial ~170 µm (epidermis)** ✅ | **deeper ~300–400 µm (mid-dermis)** ✅ |\n| **Primary target** | **epidermal melanin / pigment** | **dermal collagen + sebaceous glands** |\n| **Treats (evidence-backed)** | melasma, PIH, lentigines, diffuse dyspigmentation, photodamage, dullness, \"glow\" | inflammatory acne, atrophic acne scars, fine wrinkles, redness/porphyrin, collagen |\n| **Does it treat brown pigment?** | **Yes — this is its main job** ✅ | **No — essentially off-target** ✅ |\n| **FDA-cleared for** | photodamage/pigment (in-office systems) | **acne, atrophic acne scars, fine wrinkles** |\n| **In-office examples** | C+B Perméa, Sciton Moxi, LaseMD | C+B Original, Cynosure Smoothbeam/Affirm |\n| **Home examples** | YDUNVIE **Dora** ⚠️ (unverified) | **Tria FRX** ✅, YDUNVIE **Iris** ⚠️, **NIRA** (non-fractional) |\n\n---\n\n## 2. The pigment evidence (1927nm) — strong and directly on your goal ✅\n\nThis is a genuinely well-studied wavelength for pigmentation, including in **darker / pigment-prone skin** (directly relevant to you, given your PIH concern):\n\n- **Melasma:** retrospective study of **100 patients**, 1927nm fractional thulium → significant MASI improvement. ✅ (PubMed 31690148)\n- **Facial hyperpigmentation / melasma in *darker* skin (Fitz III–V):** 1927nm diode (± topical hydroquinone) produced **significant improvement by 4 weeks, maintained at 12 weeks**; PGA ≈ **~50% improvement** in hyperpigmentation. ✅ (PubMed 29659405)\n- **PIH in skin of color:** 1927nm thulium **successfully treated PIH** in Fitzpatrick skin of color. ✅ (PMC8016558)\n- **Diffuse dyspigmentation + actinic/photodamage:** fractionated 1927nm effective for diffuse pigment *and* sun damage. ✅ (Vingan 2023, *Lasers Surg Med*)\n- **Asian photoaging (Fitz II–IV):** prospective study — effective and safe, **no PIH observed**. ✅ (PMC10025463 / Frontiers 2023)\n- **Head-to-head physics vs 1550nm:** 1927nm's far higher water absorption makes it **superior for epidermal pigment/dyschromia**; 1550nm is for deeper dermal concerns. ✅ (multiple reviews)\n\n**Translation:** for brown pigment, dyschromia, melasma, PIH, dullness, and general photodamage/\"glow,\" **1927nm is the evidence-based wavelength** — and it has specific data in pigment-prone skin types, which matters for you.\n\n---\n\n## 3. The collagen/acne evidence (1450nm) — also strong, but for *different* problems ✅\n\n1450nm is well-validated — just not for pigment:\n\n- **FDA-cleared** for **acne, atrophic acne scars, and fine wrinkles.** ✅\n- **Histology:** causes thermal damage to collagen + sebaceous glands; produces **increased dermal collagen, elastin, and mucin** — i.e. real remodeling. ✅ (1450nm rejuvenation studies)\n- **Acne:** long-term remission of inflammatory acne; **reduces redness and porphyrin density.** ✅ (PMC1936301, PMC10342391)\n- **Rhytids/texture:** efficacy for facial wrinkles and atrophic scars. ✅\n\n**What's missing from that list: pigmentation.** 1450nm doesn't target melanin; at best it nudges *redness/inflammatory* discoloration, not brown spots. So if you bought a 1450nm device hoping to fix pigment, you'd be using the wrong tool — even though it's a \"well-researched\" tool.\n\n---\n\n## 4. \"But I want better future results / overall skin quality\" — the prejuvenation question\n\nThis is the real argument *for* 1450nm in your case, so let's be honest about it:\n\n- ✅ **Collagen does start declining ~age 25 (~1%/yr)** — so the biological premise of \"start early\" is real.\n- ⚠️ **But the evidence that *preventative laser* in healthy young skin pays off is thin.** The strongest \"prejuvenation\" data is for **preventative Botox** (muscle/wrinkle), *not* laser. Most \"start in your 20s\" laser content is **clinic-marketing**, not RCTs. Collagen-building lasers are proven to *treat* existing damage, not well-proven to *prevent* it in 25-year-olds with none.\n- 🔍 **At 25 with no wrinkles, the marginal benefit of deep 1450nm collagen work is modest** — you'd be treating a problem you don't have yet, while accepting the deeper thermal injury (and, in pigment-prone skin, higher PIH risk from going deeper).\n- ✅ **Crucially, 1927nm is *also* a skin-quality/photoaging tool**, not just spot-removal — it improves texture, tone, dullness, and subclinical photodamage. So choosing 1927nm does **not** mean giving up \"overall skin quality\"; it means addressing the surface/pigment/photoaging layer that actually matters at your age.\n\n**Best-practice sequencing:** address **pigment + photoaging now (1927nm)**; layer in **collagen work (1450/1550nm, microneedling-RF, retinoids) in your 30s** when collagen decline is clinically meaningful. You don't have to buy the collagen solution at 25 to \"future-proof.\"\n\n---\n\n## 5. PIH risk — the deciding safety factor for pigment-prone skin\n\nBoth wavelengths can trigger PIH in melanin-rich/pigment-prone skin (your situation). The nuance:\n\n- **1927nm is superficial** — less deep thermal load — and is the **most-studied wavelength for *safely* treating pigment in Fitz III–VI**, *specifically when used low-energy + low-density + with topical adjuncts* (hydroquinone/retinoid pre/post). ✅ Multiple studies report no PIH with proper low-density protocols.\n- **But melasma/PIH can *rebound*** after any 1927nm treatment if too aggressive — this is the #1 documented downside. ✅\n- **1450nm goes deeper** → in pigment-prone skin, deeper thermal injury can mean *more* PIH risk, for a benefit (collagen) you don't currently need.\n\n**Implication:** for your skin, **1927nm done conservatively** is both the on-target *and* the lower-deep-injury choice — *provided* settings are gentle and you pair it with photoprotection + topicals. Aggressive anything is the enemy.\n\n> **This is reinforced by the staggering research** ([08 §3c](08_clear_brilliant_quantified_gap.md)): for pigment, *density drives PIH more than energy*, and **low-density-over-more-sessions matches high-density-fewer-sessions on efficacy with *less* PIH** (mini-NAFR = full-NAFR, lower PIH, in skin of color). So the gentle-repeated cadence — which is exactly how home devices work — is the *standard of care* for pigment, not a compromise. A single aggressive session can even *worsen* melasma. The catch remains the home device's **unverified (likely low) density/dose** — not depth, which at a given wavelength is the same as the clinic's; and for pigment a *shallow* 1927nm is exactly what you want anyway. So the home paradigm is on the right side of the evidence.\n\n---\n\n## 6. The practical catch: evidence-best wavelength ≠ best home hardware\n\nHere's the tension you have to weigh:\n\n| | Evidence for **your goal** | Best *in-office* device | Best *home* device |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **1927nm** | ★★★★ (pigment) | C+B Perméa / Moxi / LaseMD (well-validated) | YDUNVIE **Dora** ⚠️ **unverified**; no FDA-cleared, spec-confirmed home 1927nm I can vouch for |\n| **1450nm** | ★ (pigment) / ★★★★ (collagen-acne) | C+B Original | **Tria FRX** ✅ FDA-cleared, real company |\n\nSo: the wavelength with the **best evidence for your goal (1927nm)** currently has the **weakest/least-verified *home* device (Dora)**, while the **best-verified home device (Tria FRX, 1450nm)** is the **wrong wavelength for pigment.** This is the crux of your decision.\n\n---\n\n## 7. My recommendation for you\n\n**Primary recommendation: go 1927nm — but get it in-office first, not from an unverified home device.**\n\nReasoning, ranked:\n1. **Your #1 concern is pigment, and 1927nm is the evidence-based pigment wavelength.** 1450nm won't fix brown pigment no matter how well-researched it is for other things.\n2. **At 25, you don't need deep collagen remodeling yet** — and 1927nm still covers photoaging/texture/glow, so you're not sacrificing \"overall skin quality.\"\n3. **For pigment-prone skin, superficial + conservative 1927nm is the safer-targeted choice** (with topicals + SPF).\n4. **The home 1927nm hardware (Dora) is unverified**, so the highest-confidence path is a **short in-office Perméa/Moxi/LaseMD course** (or a derm consult), *then* maintain with topicals — rather than gambling on an unverified home laser for your most PIH-sensitive goal.\n\n**Decision matrix:**\n\n| If your priority is… | Pick | Form |\n|----------------------|------|------|\n| **Pigment / PIH / brightness / tone** (your stated goal) | **1927nm** | in-office Perméa/Moxi/LaseMD; home Dora only if specs verified |\n| Acne / oil / active breakouts | 1450nm | Tria FRX / in-office |\n| Texture / pores / atrophic scars / fine lines | 1450nm (or 1550nm) | Tria FRX / in-office |\n| \"Future-proof collagen\" with no current concern | *defer* | topicals (retinoid) now; laser in 30s |\n| Want **both** in one go | **dual 1550/1927** | in-office only (Fraxel Dual / dual systems) |\n\n**And the meta-point that still wins:** for pigment specifically, the highest-ROI, lowest-PIH-risk move remains **iron-oxide tinted SPF + topicals (azelaic acid, tranexamic acid, niacinamide, retinoid)** as the base, with 1927nm as the *adjunct* — not the other way around (parent [07](../01_ipl_hair_removal/07_alternatives_and_strategy.md)). A laser without daily photoprotection will re-pigment.\n\n---\n\n## 8. TL;DR\n\n- **1450nm is better-researched — for acne/scars/fine-lines/collagen, NOT for pigment.** Don't let \"more research-backed\" mislead you; it's research on a different problem.\n- **For your pigment goal, 1927nm is clearly the evidence-based wavelength**, with strong data including pigment-prone skin.\n- **At 25, the collagen (\"prejuvenation\") case for 1450nm is real-but-thin** and addresses a problem you don't have yet; 1927nm also improves overall photoaging/skin quality, so you lose little.\n- **Safety:** conservative 1927nm + topicals + SPF is the on-target, lower-deep-injury route for pigment-prone skin.\n- **Practical snag:** the best home *device* (Tria, 1450nm) is the wrong wavelength; the right wavelength's home device (Dora, 1927nm) is unverified — so **favor in-office 1927nm** for the pigment work, or verify a Dora rigorously before trusting it.\n\n---\n\n### Sources\n- [1927nm thulium for melasma — 100 patients (PubMed 31690148)](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31690148/)\n- [1927nm diode ± hydroquinone for hyperpigmentation/melasma in *darker skin* (PubMed 29659405)](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29659405/)\n- [1927nm thulium treats PIH in skin of color (PMC8016558)](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8016558/)\n- [Fractionated 1927nm for diffuse dyspigmentation + actinic changes (Vingan 2023)](https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/full/10.1002/lsm.23653)\n- [1927nm fractional thulium in Asian photoaging — safety/no PIH (PMC10025463)](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10025463/)\n- [Low-density 1927nm for hyperpigmented scars, Fitz II–V (PubMed 36054056)](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/36054056/)\n- [1450nm diode for acne — open study (PMC1936301)](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC1936301/) · [1450nm reduces redness/porphyrin (PMC10342391)](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10342391/) · [1450nm nonablative rejuvenation (PubMed 16176775)](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/16176775/)\n- [Dual 1550/1927nm NAFL review (PubMed 40635144)](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/40635144/)\n- Prejuvenation: collagen decline from ~25 (~1%/yr); strongest preventative evidence is for Botox, not laser — clinic/derm summaries (⚠️ low-grade evidence)\n", "file": "09_1927nm_vs_1450nm_headtohead.md"}, {"id": "doc10", "md": "# Where to Buy: Storefront Directory\n\nEvery storefront I could find selling each device in [03_device_landscape](03_device_landscape.md), with **special depth on YDUNVIE models**. Snapshot **June 2026** — prices/stock change. I did **not** place orders or independently vet each seller's legitimacy beyond what's publicly visible; treat unverified resellers with the cautions in §6.\n\n**Trust legend:** ✅ brand-official/direct · 🟡 authorized reseller (claimed) · 🔵 major marketplace (Amazon/eBay) · ⚠️ dropship/unverified storefront · ♻️ used/secondhand only · 🏭 B2B (not consumer) · 💱 USD at ~¥7.2/$1.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Master buying table\n\n| Device | Official / direct | Marketplaces | Resellers | Used | Status |\n|--------|-------------------|--------------|-----------|------|--------|\n| **Clear + Brilliant / Perméa** | in-office only (find a provider) | — | — | RockBottomLasers (used *machines*) ♻️ | not a consumer device |\n| **Tria FRX** | [trialaser.com](https://www.trialaser.com/products/frx-fractional-skin-rejuvenating-laser) ✅ $699.99 | Amazon 🔵, eBay 🔵 | skincarebyalana, yourbeautygadgets 🟡 | eBay ♻️ | **on sale** |\n| **NIRA Pro / Pro 3 / Precision** | [niraskin.com](https://www.niraskin.com/) ✅ | Amazon (NIRA official store) 🔵, eBay 🔵 | us.yonka.com, simplebeautyminerals 🟡 | eBay ♻️ | **on sale** |\n| **LYMA Laser / PRO** | [us.lyma.life](https://us.lyma.life/products/lyma-laser-us) ✅ ~$2,695 | — | Dermstore, VioletGrey, Face the Future, Diamond Face Inst. 🟡 | — | **on sale** |\n| **JOVS 4D Laser Mask** | [jovs.com](https://jovs.com/products/4d-laser-light-therapy-mask) ✅ $729–1,268; [eu.jovs.com](https://eu.jovs.com/) | Amazon (JOVS official store) 🔵 | — | — | **on sale** (PBM, not resurfacing) |\n| **DermRays Revive** | [dermrays.com](https://www.dermrays.com/products/dermrays-revive/) ✅ | Amazon (DermRays store) 🔵, eBay 🔵 | namamausa, ShopMy 🟡⚠️ | — | **on sale** (1064nm, Rx-class) |\n| **Iluminage Skin Smoothing Laser** | (brand defunct) | [Amazon B00RXZHZK8](https://www.amazon.com/iluminage-Anti-Aging-FDA-cleared-Smoothing-Laser/dp/B00RXZHZK8) 🔵, eBay (incl. \"2.0\") 🔵 | myernk ⚠️ (~$598, US-only) | eBay ♻️ | clearance/old stock |\n| **PaloVia** | discontinued | eBay (new-in-box + used) ♻️🔵 | — | eBay ♻️ | **discontinued** |\n| **Philips RéAura SC5000** | discontinued | eBay (refurb, 2-yr warranty) ♻️🔵 | — | eBay ♻️ | **discontinued** |\n| **YDUNVIE family** | see §2 (China-direct) | Lazada, Facebook Mktp, TikTok 🔵⚠️ | myernk, GlamGlobal, Sherue, HALOHK, Jofiou, COSA, MimiSilk, OYAY | Facebook ♻️ | **on sale** (see §2) |\n| **Focuslight 1470nm module** | [focuslight.com](https://focuslight.com/application/medical-health/skin-rejuvenation/) — \"contact sales\" 🏭 | — | — | — | **B2B only, no consumer purchase** |\n\n---\n\n## 2. YDUNVIE / 易科美 — full storefront breakdown (your priority)\n\nYDUNVIE sells through **China-direct channels** (cheapest), **cross-border/HK resellers**, and **Western relabels**. Same hardware, very different price and support. (Brand = Jiangsu Unimed; USPTO trademark [88541477](https://uspto.report/TM/88541477).)\n\n### 2a. China-direct (cheapest; need a forwarder/proxy buyer)\n| Storefront | Models / price | Trust |\n|-----------|----------------|-------|\n| **ydunvie.com.cn** (official) / **ydunvie.com** (English info) | full catalog | ✅ official |\n| **Tmall 易科美旗舰店** (flagship) | A9/A7/A8 with coupons | ✅ official store |\n| **JD / 京东** ([item.jd.com](https://item.jd.com/2198175.html)) | Iris ~¥2,108–3,988 (≈$293–$554) | ✅ |\n| **Suning** ([product.suning.com](https://product.suning.com/0000000000/165376307.html)) | Iris fractional | 🟡 |\n| **Kaola / 考拉海购** ([brand 107053](https://search.kaola.com/brand/107053.html)) | cross-border haitao | 🟡 |\n| **SMZDM** ([pinpai.smzdm.com/61601](https://pinpai.smzdm.com/61601/)) | deal tracker (not a store) — A9 ~¥2,788 (≈$387), low ~¥1,396 (≈$194) | price reference |\n| **Dealmoon** [US](https://www.dealmoon.com/product/-ydunvie-a7-iris/3541987) / [CA](https://www.dealmoon.ca/product/-ydunvie-a7-iris/2129776) | A7-Iris ¥5,982 (≈$831) / CA$3,988 | price reference |\n\n### 2b. Cross-border / HK resellers (ship internationally, English support)\n| Storefront | Models / price | Trust |\n|-----------|----------------|-------|\n| **myernk.com** ([Iris Ice](https://myernk.com/products/fractional-laser-beauty-machine-dermabrasion-machine-acne-pits-improvement-pores-lightening-crows-feet) ~$580; [YDUNVIE collection](https://myernk.com/collections/ydunvie); also Dora/A8, Iluminage) | claims **\"authorized agent,\" 12-mo warranty, 130 countries** | 🟡 (best of the resellers) |\n| **GlamGlobal** [UK](https://glamglobal.co.uk/products/fractional-laser-beauty-machine-dermabrasion-machine-acne-pits-improvement-pores-lightening-crows-feet) / [US](https://glamglobal.com/products/fractional-laser-beauty-machine-dermabrasion-machine-acne-pits-improvement-pores-lightening-crows-feet) | Ice Crystal (A9) | ⚠️ (same product listing/slug as myernk → likely dropship) |\n| **Sherue** ([sherue.com](https://sherue.com/products/fractional-laser-beauty-machine-dermabrasion-machine-acne-pits-improvement-pores-lightening-crows-feet)) | Ice Crystal (A9) | ⚠️ (same slug — dropship pattern) |\n| **HALOHK** ([halohk.com](https://halohk.com/en/blogs/news/)) | Ice Crystal (A9) blog+shop | 🟡 HK |\n| **Jofiou Beauty** ([jofioubeauty.com](https://www.jofioubeauty.com/zh-usa/products/ydunvie-%E6%98%93%E7%A7%91%E7%BE%8E%E5%A4%A7%E7%99%BD%E7%B4%8D%E7%B1%B3%E9%9B%B7%E5%B0%84%E6%BF%80%E5%85%89%E7%85%A5%E8%86%9A%E5%84%80-%E5%8E%BB%E9%9B%80%E6%96%91-%E7%BE%8E%E7%99%BD%E6%8F%90%E4%BA%AE%E5%AE%B6%E7%94%A8%E7%BE%8E%E5%AE%B9%E5%84%80-1)) | **A8 Dora \"大白\" 1927nm ~$719** | 🟡 (a rare Dora source) |\n| **COSA HK** ([cosahk.com](https://cosahk.com/shop/%E6%98%93%E7%A7%91%E7%BE%8E-ydunvie-%E7%B4%8D%E7%B1%B3%E9%BB%9E%E9%99%A3%E5%AB%A9%E8%86%9A%E7%BE%8E%E5%AE%B9%E5%84%80%E5%99%A8/)) | Iris (A7) | 🟡 HK |\n\n### 2c. Western relabels (turnkey, English warranty, premium price)\n| Storefront | Model | Price | Trust |\n|-----------|-------|-------|-------|\n| **MimiSilk** ([mimisilk.com](https://www.mimisilk.com/products/mimisilk-iris-1450nm-advanced-skin-renewing-device)) | \"Iris\" = **A7 Iris (1450nm)** rebadge | $599 (reg $699); 2-yr warranty + 90-day refund | ⚠️ (markets as \"Danish\"; no disclosed YDUNVIE link or K-number) |\n| **OYAY** | \"Iris Ice Plus\" (A9) / \"Dora\" (A8) | Iris Ice Plus **$999** | ⚠️ dropship storefront (Shopify; verify authorization) |\n\n### 2d. Marketplaces\n- **Lazada** (SG/MY): \"[Ydunvie A9 Ice Crystal Dot Matrix Laser](https://www.lazada.sg/products/ydunvie-a9-ice-crystal-dot-matrix-laser-beauty-meter-ipl-device-shrink-pores-flat-pox-pits-light-acne-marks-ydunvie-i3209669909.html)\" 🔵⚠️\n- **Facebook Marketplace** (e.g. Waterloo ON listing) — secondhand ♻️\n- **TikTok Shop** — Ice Crystal listings 🔵⚠️\n\n### Per-model \"where to buy\" cheat sheet\n| Model | Best China-direct | Best intl reseller | Western relabel |\n|-------|-------------------|--------------------|-----------------|\n| **A7 Iris** (1450nm base) | JD/Tmall ~¥2,108–3,998 (≈$293–$555) | COSA / myernk | **MimiSilk $599** |\n| **A9 Iris Ice** (1450nm flagship) | Tmall ~¥2,788–4,588 (≈$387–$637) | **myernk ~$580**, HALOHK | OYAY \"Iris Ice Plus\" $999 |\n| **A8 Dora** (1927nm — your pigment pick) | Tmall ~¥2,300 (≈$319) | **Jofiou ~$719**, myernk | OYAY \"Dora\" |\n| **Iris Mini** | imeirongyi ~¥2,300 (≈$319) | — | — |\n\n> **For your 1927nm (Dora) goal:** the realistic buyable storefronts are **Jofiou (~$719)**, **myernk**, or China-direct. There is *no* mainstream Western retailer for the 1927nm model — MimiSilk only sells the 1450nm Iris. Verify the **rating-label wavelength is actually 1927nm** before paying (the listings have a recurring 1450/1927 copy inconsistency — see [05](05_ydunvie_catalog.md)).\n\n---\n\n## 3. Branded devices — purchase detail\n\n- **Tria FRX** — [trialaser.com](https://www.trialaser.com/products/frx-fractional-skin-rejuvenating-laser) **$699.99** (free shipping), the safe primary source; also Amazon, eBay, and beauty resellers (skincarebyalana, yourbeautygadgets). *The one FDA-cleared home fractional with a real brand behind it.*\n- **NIRA Pro 3 / Pro / Precision** — [niraskin.com](https://www.niraskin.com/) + **NIRA official store on Amazon** (legit channel), plus us.yonka.com and simplebeautyminerals. (Non-fractional — maintenance, not resurfacing.)\n- **LYMA Laser / PRO** — [us.lyma.life](https://us.lyma.life/) ~**$2,695**, plus Dermstore, VioletGrey, Face the Future, Diamond Face Institute; brand [store locator](https://lyma.life/en-us/pages/store-locator). (LLLT/PBM — different category.)\n- **JOVS 4D Laser Mask** — [jovs.com](https://jovs.com/products/4d-laser-light-therapy-mask) **$729–1,268** + JOVS official Amazon store + [eu.jovs.com](https://eu.jovs.com/). (VCSEL PBM mask, not resurfacing.)\n- **DermRays Revive** — [dermrays.com](https://www.dermrays.com/products/dermrays-revive/) + Amazon (DermRays store) + eBay. (1064nm, Rx-class — different mechanism.)\n- **Iluminage Skin Smoothing Laser** — brand defunct; buy via **Amazon** ([B00RXZHZK8](https://www.amazon.com/iluminage-Anti-Aging-FDA-cleared-Smoothing-Laser/dp/B00RXZHZK8)) or **eBay** (incl. a \"2.0\" listing) and the myernk listing (~$598, US-only). *Recall the FDA-vs-listing fractional discrepancy — see [03](03_device_landscape.md).*\n\n---\n\n## 4. Discontinued — secondhand only\n\n- **PaloVia Skin Renewing Laser** — **eBay only**; multiple new-in-box and pre-owned units + pre-treatment gel still circulate. The purest \"home Fraxel\" relic; collector/study buy.\n- **Philips RéAura SC5000** — **eBay**; refurbished units (one with a 2-yr warranty) and unused performance gel appear. Note historical user-forum safety complaints; buy informed.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Not buyable as a consumer\n\n- **Clear + Brilliant / Perméa** — in-office only; book a provider. (Used *machines* appear on dealer sites like RockBottomLasers — clinic equipment, not for home.)\n- **Focuslight 1470nm module** — [focuslight.com](https://focuslight.com/application/medical-health/skin-rejuvenation/) is **B2B**; the only path is \"contact sales\" to commission/OEM. No price, no MOQ, no consumer SKU. (See [04 §2a](04_suppliers_and_companies.md).)\n\n---\n\n## 6. How to buy without getting burned\n\n1. **Prefer brand-official or \"authorized agent\" with a warranty + return policy.** For YDUNVIE that's China-direct (Tmall flagship) or **myernk** (claims authorized, 12-mo warranty); for branded devices, the brand site or its official Amazon store.\n2. **Watch for the dropship tell:** GlamGlobal, Sherue, and others share the **identical product slug** `fractional-laser-beauty-machine-dermabrasion-machine-...` — that's a re-listed dropship product, not an authorized stock holder. Same goes for OYAY.\n3. **Demand the K-number + rating label** before paying premium for any \"FDA-cleared\" claim (MimiSilk/OYAY don't publish one; likely lean on Jiangsu Unimed K182498).\n4. **Confirm wavelength on the label** — critical for the **1927nm Dora** (recurring 1450/1927 copy error).\n5. **Price anchors:** China-direct A9 ≈ ¥3,000–3,400 (≈$417–$472). If a Western store charges $999 (OYAY) for the same hardware, you're paying ~2× for support/markup — fine if you want returns, bad if you assumed it was \"better.\"\n6. **Used PaloVia/RéAura:** buy only with photos of a working unit + (for RéAura) the gel, since these are consumables-dependent.\n\n---\n\n### Sources\n- YDUNVIE: [myernk](https://myernk.com/collections/ydunvie) · [GlamGlobal UK](https://glamglobal.co.uk/) · [Sherue](https://sherue.com/) · [Jofiou (Dora/A8)](https://www.jofioubeauty.com/) · [COSA HK](https://cosahk.com/) · [JD](https://item.jd.com/2198175.html) · [Dealmoon](https://www.dealmoon.com/product/-ydunvie-a7-iris/3541987) · [MimiSilk](https://www.mimisilk.com/products/mimisilk-iris-1450nm-advanced-skin-renewing-device) · [USPTO TM 88541477](https://uspto.report/TM/88541477)\n- Branded: [Tria FRX](https://www.trialaser.com/products/frx-fractional-skin-rejuvenating-laser) · [NIRA](https://www.niraskin.com/) · [LYMA](https://us.lyma.life/) · [JOVS](https://jovs.com/products/4d-laser-light-therapy-mask) · [DermRays](https://www.dermrays.com/products/dermrays-revive/) · [Iluminage (Amazon)](https://www.amazon.com/iluminage-Anti-Aging-FDA-cleared-Smoothing-Laser/dp/B00RXZHZK8)\n- Discontinued: PaloVia (eBay) · [Philips RéAura SC5000 refurb (eBay)](https://www.ebay.com/itm/205109353135)\n- B2B: [Focuslight skin rejuvenation](https://focuslight.com/application/medical-health/skin-rejuvenation/)\n", "file": "10_where_to_buy_storefronts.md"}, {"id": "doc11", "md": "# Subscriber Q&A: Can frequent low-density at-home laser = meaningful rejuvenation?\n\nA reader question (good one — it gets the physics mostly right), plus **how a laser-specialty dermatologist would likely answer, and why.** The answer is reconstructed from the evidence in [08](08_clear_brilliant_quantified_gap.md) and [09](09_1927nm_vs_1450nm_headtohead.md) and reflects mainstream laser-derm consensus — it is *not* a quote from a specific named physician, and isn't individual medical advice.\n\n---\n\n## The question (as received)\n\n> \"I had a question about at-home 1440–1450 nm non-ablative fractional lasers like MimiSilk Iris and Tria FRX. My understanding is that their per-microbeam energy overlaps with Clear + Brilliant Original (C+B: 4–9 mJ; some at-home devices: ~5–12 mJ), with the main difference being per-session coverage/density (~0.3–1.5% at-home vs C+B: ~5–10%). So in theory, around a month of at-home sessions could cumulatively approach one session of Clear + Brilliant from a coverage standpoint.\n>\n> In your opinion, can frequent low-density at-home treatments produce meaningful rejuvenation over time, or do they fall short because of the sparse daily MTZs not creating the same remodeling response? … can at-home devices actually be meaningful rejuvenation tools, or is it more maintenance?\"\n\n**What the reader gets right (give them credit):** the per-microbeam **energy** overlap is real, and so — at matched wavelength — is **depth** and even per-column **fluence** (a small home spot can hit *higher* J/cm² than C+B; see [08 §4b](08_clear_brilliant_quantified_gap.md)). And the cumulative-**coverage** arithmetic is roughly correct: at ~0.44%/session it takes ~24 sessions to equal one C+B-high session's surface coverage — about a month of near-daily use ([08 §3c](08_clear_brilliant_quantified_gap.md)).\n\n---\n\n## How a laser-specialty dermatologist would likely respond\n\n> \"You've actually got the engineering right, and that's where most people stop — so let me answer the part that matters: **cumulative coverage is not the same as cumulative remodeling.** You can match the *surface area* C+B treats in a month of home sessions and still not reproduce its *result*, because the dermis doesn't integrate a hundred tiny, fully-healed pinpricks the way it responds to one denser field of injury delivered at once.\n>\n> Think about *how* a fractional laser works. Each microthermal zone is a column of injury surrounded by intact skin; the **untreated tissue between columns is what drives the repair signal** — fibroblast activation, heat-shock proteins, the neocollagenesis cascade that builds over weeks to months. That signaling is **density-dependent and somewhat threshold-dependent within a single healing window.** A session at 5–10% coverage creates a confluent, robust wound-healing response across the treated zone. A home session at 0.3–1.5% creates a handful of isolated columns that **re-epithelialize in about a day and largely resolve before the next session** — so each session is its own small, sub-confluent event rather than a building block stacking onto the last. You're not 'banking' coverage toward a remodeling threshold; you're repeatedly tickling it.\n>\n> So my honest answer in two parts:\n>\n> **For collagen/texture (which is exactly what 1440–1450 nm targets):** these devices fall meaningfully short of an in-office series for *structural* change — deeper wrinkles, acne scars, real dermal remodeling. The comparative data backs this up: when you actually test high-density vs low-density at matched total dose, **high-density wins for dermal/scar remodeling.** Frequency partially compensates, never fully. I'd call a home 1450 nm device a **maintenance and mild-improvement tool**, not a Clear + Brilliant substitute.\n>\n> **For pigment, tone, glow, and 'skin quality':** the picture is more favorable — but notice that's mostly an **epidermal** effect (turnover, brightening, light textural polish), and the wavelength that excels there is **1927 nm**, not the 1440/1450 nm you asked about. For superficial pigment, low-and-slow is genuinely the right approach, and home devices can be legitimately useful. Ironically, the devices in your question are tuned for the *collagen* job, which is the job where per-session density matters most.\n>\n> **Net:** yes, meaningful — but **modest, mostly superficial, and maintenance-leaning.** Real rejuvenation in my chair is the in-office series doing the heavy structural work, with a home device extending and maintaining it between visits. And whatever device you use, the unglamorous truth is that **daily SPF + a retinoid + topicals will out-perform the laser for overall skin quality** — the laser is the adjunct, not the engine. Two practical caveats that shrink real-world home results further: almost nobody sustains daily use for months, and hand-gliding gives uneven, drifting coverage that a clinic's optical scanner doesn't.\"\n\n---\n\n## Why they'd say that — the mechanistic reasoning (the \"why\")\n\n1. **Coverage ≠ remodeling (the core correction).** Remodeling is driven by the **density/confluence of injury within one healing window**, not by an integral of surface coverage over months. Many sparse, independently-healed MTZs ≠ one dense field. ([08 §3b/§3c](08_clear_brilliant_quantified_gap.md))\n2. **Injuries don't \"bank.\"** Skin fully re-epithelializes (<24 h) and resolves between sessions, so home injuries reset rather than accumulate toward a threshold — the cumulative-coverage formula (1−(1−C)ⁿ) describes *spatial area touched*, not *remodeling delivered*. ([08 §3c](08_clear_brilliant_quantified_gap.md))\n3. **The gap is density + dose control, not energy/depth/diameter.** Per-column, home matches (or exceeds) C+B on energy, wavelength-set depth, and fluence; it loses on **how much skin per session** and **uniform, supervised, escalating dosing to an endpoint.** ([08 §1, §4, §4b](08_clear_brilliant_quantified_gap.md))\n4. **Direct comparative evidence (the answer splits by goal):**\n   - *Collagen/scars →* high-density beats low-density: [hypertrophic-scar RCT, p<0.001 (PubMed 31851017)](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31851017/); [CO₂ split-face, higher-fluence/lower-density wins (PubMed 21070459)](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/21070459/).\n   - *Pigment →* low-density-more-sessions *matches* high-density-fewer with less PIH: [Chan et al., mini-NAFR = full-NAFR, lower PIH (PubMed 21246574)](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/21246574/); [Brauer et al., low-energy/low-density 1927nm, *JDD* (PubMed 26580875)](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26580875/); [Bae et al., 1927nm for PIH in darker skin (PubMed 31663147)](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31663147/). Full list in [08 §3c](08_clear_brilliant_quantified_gap.md).\n5. **Wavelength mismatch in the question:** 1440/1450 nm = collagen/texture (deeper, density-hungry); the home-friendly \"skin quality\" wins are largely epidermal and belong to 1927 nm. ([09](09_1927nm_vs_1450nm_headtohead.md))\n6. **Real-world compliance + technique** erode the theoretical case: sustained daily months are rare, and manual coverage drifts/defocuses (uneven dose). ([08 §4b, §5](08_clear_brilliant_quantified_gap.md))\n\n---\n\n## Bottom line\n\n| Question | Laser-derm's likely verdict |\n|----------|-----------------------------|\n| Can frequent low-density home sessions produce *meaningful* rejuvenation? | **Yes — but modest and mostly superficial** (glow, tone, light texture, mild cumulative collagen). |\n| Do they fall short of in-office because MTZs are too sparse? | **Yes, for structural/dermal remodeling** — sparse independently-healed columns don't reproduce a dense session's repair cascade. |\n| Rejuvenation tool or maintenance? | **Primarily maintenance + prevention + mild improvement**; best as an adjunct that *extends* an in-office series, not a replacement. |\n| Does \"a month of coverage = one C+B session\" hold? | **On surface area, roughly. On *result*, no** — coverage isn't remodeling. |\n| Biggest lever for the reader's actual goal? | **Topicals + SPF + retinoid** do the heavy lifting; pick wavelength to the goal (1927 nm if pigment-led). |\n\n---\n\n## If drafting a short public reply (concise version)\n\n> \"Great question — your physics is right! Energy, depth, and even per-spot fluence are similar between these home devices and Clear + Brilliant. The catch is that *coverage isn't the same as remodeling.* C+B treats 5–10% of your skin in one dense session, triggering a strong, confluent collagen-building response; a home device treats <1.5% as scattered columns that heal in a day and reset before the next session — so you're repeatedly tapping the door rather than knocking it down. Result: home 1450 nm devices are **real but modest — maintenance + glow + mild texture**, not a swap for an in-office series (especially for deeper wrinkles or scars). They shine most as *between-treatment maintenance*, and honestly your retinoid + daily SPF will out-pull either for overall skin quality. If pigment is your main concern, look at 1927 nm rather than 1450 nm. 💛\"\n\n*(General education, not medical advice — individual candidacy/settings should be assessed by a provider, especially for pigment-prone skin where PIH risk is real.)*\n\n---\n\n### Cross-references\n- [08 — the quantified gap](08_clear_brilliant_quantified_gap.md) (§3b density math, §3c staggering research, §4 depth=wavelength, §4b microbeam diameter)\n- [09 — 1927nm vs 1450nm](09_1927nm_vs_1450nm_headtohead.md) (why pigment vs collagen changes the answer)\n- [02 — in-office vs at-home expectations](02_in_office_vs_at_home.md)\n", "file": "11_subscriber_qa_lowdensity_rejuvenation.md"}, {"id": "doc12", "md": "# Alibaba Supplier Scan (live browse)\n\n**Method:** browsed Alibaba.com live via the Chrome extension on **2026-06-21**, searching \"1450nm fractional laser home,\" \"1927nm fractional laser home use,\" \"Focuslight 1470nm laser module,\" and the Suppliers tab for \"unimed laser.\" Prices are as-listed (USD), MOQ-dependent, and change constantly. This confirms/extends [04_suppliers_and_companies](04_suppliers_and_companies.md) and [10_where_to_buy_storefronts](10_where_to_buy_storefronts.md).\n\n---\n\n## 1. Headline findings\n\n1. **There is NO consumer *handheld* 1450/1927nm fractional device on Alibaba** — nothing in the YDUNVIE Iris / MimiSilk / Tria FRX class. Every \"fractional\" result is a **clinic/salon machine** ($890–$42,000), an **OEM laser module/source**, or an **IPL hair-removal handheld**. This directly confirms md04's call: the home fractional handhelds are **brand-controlled, not open Alibaba SKUs.**\n2. **Jiangsu Unimed / YDUNVIE has NO findable Alibaba storefront.** A Suppliers-tab search for \"unimed laser\" returned only unrelated firms (Hebei JT Medical; \"Suzhou Unimes\" = POS terminals). → To buy the Iris/Dora you still go YDUNVIE/MimiSilk direct (md10), not Alibaba.\n3. **Focuslight has NO Alibaba storefront either** — consistent with it being a large public B2B company that sells via its own sales team. But Alibaba has **many alternative 1470nm/1440nm laser-module suppliers** if you want to commission a build (see §4).\n4. **\"Home use\" on Alibaba is marketing.** Several $6k–$12k standing/portable *clinic* machines are titled \"for Home Use\" (Beijing Superlaser, PZ Laser). They are not consumer devices.\n5. **Most \"1470nm\" hits are endolaser/lipolysis** (980+1470nm fat-dissolving/vein), **not** fractional skin resurfacing. Only Gigaalaser and Shandong Huamei sell 1470nm *fractional skin* units. Don't confuse the two.\n\n---\n\n## 2. md04 suppliers CONFIRMED with live Alibaba stores ✅\n\n| Supplier | On Alibaba | Relevant product (live) | Price | Store stats |\n|----------|-----------|--------------------------|-------|-------------|\n| **Gigaalaser Company Ltd.** | ✅ | **1470nm non-ablative fractional** skin rejuvenation (\"1470nm Diode Lasers Enable Home Skin Rejuvenation\") | **$2,000–4,000** | 3 yrs, 5.0★(4), reorder 29% |\n| **Shandong Huamei Technology** | ✅ | **1470nm fractional** anti-aging (cheapest fractional found); also **1927nm thulium** fiber fractional | **$890–980** (1470nm); $11,999–13,000 (1927nm) | 9–10 yrs, 4.8–4.9★ |\n| **Beijing Superlaser Technology** | ✅ | **1927nm thulium** \"for Home Use\" fractional, acne scars | **$9,888–12,000** | 8 yrs, 4.6★(7) |\n| **Zhengzhou PZ Laser Slim Technology** | ✅ | **1927nm thulium** fractional (dullness/wrinkles/pores); CO2 fractional | **$9,000–12,000** | 16 yrs, 4.6★(21) |\n| **Shanghai Apolo Medical Technology** | ✅ (heavy ad presence) | **1550nm / 1927nm** fiber fractional; CO2 | $9,400–42,000 | 19 yrs |\n| **Hebei Keylaser Sci-Tech** | ✅ | **1927nm thulium** fiber-beam fractional, \"DIY\" | **$6,500–7,000** | 4 yrs, 5.0★(8) |\n\n**Not separately re-verified this session** (listed in md04 from prior Alibaba/Made-in-China sourcing): Guangzhou Huafei **Liton**, Beijing **HONKON**. Likely present; confirm directly if needed.\n\n**Cheapest tech-relevant fractional on Alibaba:** Shandong Huamei **1470nm fractional, $890–980** — but it's a clinic desktop unit, not a handheld.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Closest \"home / at-home\" labeled products (still not true handhelds)\n\n| Product | Supplier | Price | Reality |\n|---------|----------|-------|---------|\n| \"Advanced At-home Fractional Laser Device\" (stretch marks) | Shaanxi Yateli Technology | **$1,499** | small portable unit; verify wavelength/type (likely CO2/RF, not 1450nm NAF) |\n| \"fractional laser machine home use non ablative... 2026\" | Oman Medical Beauty (HK) | **$3,400** | desktop, non-handheld |\n| \"1927nm Thulium for Home Use\" | Beijing Superlaser / PZ Laser | $9,000–12,000 | clinic machine, \"home\" is marketing |\n| \"1927nm thulium ... Salon & Home Use\" | Hipdeer Technology (US-based) | $6,799 | clinic-grade, US seller |\n\n**None of these is a YDUNVIE-style handheld.** The genuine home handhelds remain off-Alibaba (md10).\n\n---\n\n## 4. OEM component / laser-module suppliers (the \"build your own\" path — Focuslight alternatives)\n\nFocuslight isn't on Alibaba, but its *category* is well-represented. If you ever wanted to commission a device, these sell the laser engine:\n\n| Supplier | Component | Price | Note |\n|----------|-----------|-------|------|\n| **Jlight Semiconductor** | **1440nm 5.5W laser diode chip** (single emitter) + 1470/980nm fiber modules | $5–95 (chip); $510–560 (module) | ⭐ 1440nm = the **C+B/Tria wavelength** as a bare chip |\n| **Shenzhen Super Laser Technology** | **1927nm 15W/30W thulium-doped fiber laser source** | $6,150 | the pigment-wavelength source as a module |\n| Shenzhen Starsealand Opto | 1064/1470/1550nm fiber modules 100–150W | $1,800 | industrial/medical modules |\n| Associated Opto-Electronics (Chongqing) | 1470nm box fiber-coupled modules 2–6W | $189–299 | medical-aesthetics modules |\n| Hezhou Litlight; Changsha Gomecy; Hangzhou Brandnew; Raycus (Wuhan CS Tec) | various 1440–1580nm diode/fiber modules | $50–4,300 | broad module market |\n\n> Takeaway: the **laser engine is a commodity on Alibaba** (you can even buy a 1440nm diode chip). What YDUNVIE/Tria actually sell is the **integration** — scanner, cooling, eye-safety, firmware, enclosure, regulatory clearance — which is *not* a stock Alibaba item. That's the moat, and why there's no drop-in clone.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Cross-link to the parent IPL repo\n\nThe parent repo's IPL brand **Fansizhe** (Shenzhen Fansizhe Science & Technology) appears throughout these laser searches selling its **Moolweel** IPL hair-removal handhelds ($52–65) — a reminder that the cheap \"laser\" handhelds on Alibaba are **IPL hair removal**, a different category from fractional resurfacing.\n\n---\n\n## 6. Bottom line (answering \"find anything similar / who makes md4–md10 devices\")\n\n- **Similar finished product to buy on Alibaba?** No true match. Closest *technology* = Gigaalaser / Huamei **1470nm fractional** clinic units ($890–4,000), and the **1927nm thulium** clinic machines ($6.5k–12k) from Superlaser / PZ Laser / Keylaser / Huamei — but all are **clinic/desktop, not the handheld** you researched.\n- **Who likely makes the md4/md10 devices?** The **YDUNVIE/Iris/Dora family maker (Jiangsu Unimed) is NOT on Alibaba** — it's a closed brand. The **clinic-machine suppliers in md04 ARE on Alibaba** (table §2). The **OEM laser modules** behind any of them are commodity (§4).\n- **Action if buying a finished home device:** stick with md10's channels (YDUNVIE direct / MimiSilk / myernk / Jofiou) — Alibaba won't get you the Iris or Dora.\n- **Action if exploring a clinic machine or a custom build:** Alibaba is the right place — start with **Gigaalaser (1470nm NAF)** or a **1927nm thulium** unit from Superlaser/PZ/Keylaser, and **Jlight/Shenzhen Super Laser** for modules.\n\n---\n\n### Sources (live Alibaba listings, 2026-06-21)\n- [Alibaba search: \"1450nm fractional laser home\"](https://www.alibaba.com/trade/search?SearchText=1450nm+fractional+laser+home) · [search: \"1927nm fractional laser home use\"](https://www.alibaba.com/trade/search?SearchText=1927nm+fractional+laser+home+use) · [search: \"Focuslight 1470nm laser module\"](https://www.alibaba.com/trade/search?SearchText=Focuslight+1470nm+laser+module) · [Suppliers search: \"unimed laser\"](https://www.alibaba.com/trade/search?fsb=y&IndexArea=company_en&SearchText=unimed+laser)\n- Stores observed: Gigaalaser, Shandong Huamei, Beijing Superlaser, Zhengzhou PZ Laser, Shanghai Apolo Medical, Hebei Keylaser, Jlight Semiconductor, Shenzhen Super Laser, Shenzhen Starsealand.\n", "file": "12_alibaba_supplier_scan.md"}, {"id": "doc13", "md": "# Tria SmoothBeauty™ Laser — ID, Specs & Quick-Start Owner's Guide\n\n**What this is:** the device you have in hand, fully identified and spec'd from its **primary-source manuals** (Quick Start Guide + Instructions for Use, mirrored in [`tria_smoothbeauty/source_docs/`](tria_smoothbeauty/source_docs/)), then turned into a practical \"everything you need to know to use it tonight\" guide.\n\nConfidence legend: ✅ **verified** (the IFU itself / FDA / peer-reviewed) · ⚠️ **marketing/review claim** · 🔍 **inferred** (from physics/class, see [08](08_clear_brilliant_quantified_gap.md)).\n\n---\n\n## 0. TL;DR\n\n1. **It's the Tria Age-Defying Laser under a new name.** SmoothBeauty™ Laser = **Tria Age-Defying Laser** = **Tria FRX** = model **SRL** (\"Skin Rejuvenating Laser\"). Same hardware, rebranded over time/region; your bilingual EN/FR manual is the **Canada/international** edition. ✅ FDA-cleared **Oct 30, 2013** (the repo's **K130459**). It is **not** the *only* FDA-cleared home fractional laser — **MimiSilk Iris** (✅ cleared via Jiangsu Unimed's **K182498**, \"Advanced Skin Renewing Device\") is too, and **PaloVia/RéAura** were historically. What's true: **Tria is the only one whose own brand holds a verifiable 510(k) under its own name for a currently-sold device** — the \"real company, real clearance\" pick ([03](03_device_landscape.md)/[04](04_suppliers_and_companies.md)/[README](README.md)).\n2. **Verified specs (from your IFU, p.31):** **1440 nm diode laser**, fractional non-ablative, **Class 1** (invisible beam, eye-safe by design), **5–12 mJ/pulse**, model **SRL**, 3-yr design life. ✅ — these were ⚠️ in the repo before; now they're primary-source confirmed.\n3. **Energy ≈ in-office; density is ~10–30× lower.** Per-pulse 5–12 mJ matches Clear+Brilliant's 4–9 mJ, and depth (~300–450 µm) is wavelength-locked and equal. The gap is **coverage/density** — this device lays down only **~30–180 MTZ/cm² (~0.3–1.5% coverage) per session** 🔍 vs C+B's ~650–1,270/10%. Full math in [08 §3b](08_clear_brilliant_quantified_gap.md). A web anchor corroborates the floor: at-home units \"usually do not exceed ~40 MTZ/cm².\"\n4. **It's a collagen/fine-line tool, NOT a pigment tool.** 1440 nm = water/collagen depth. The IFU's *cleared indication is periorbital wrinkles (crow's feet)*, and it **explicitly says it is not effective on dyschromia, freckles, or veins**. For *your* pigment goal it's off-target (you'd want 1927 nm — see [09](09_1927nm_vs_1450nm_headtohead.md)); for the *collagen/texture half* of your goal it's on-target.\n5. **The protocol:** cleanse → treat 4 face zones nightly → serum + AM sunscreen. **Ramp Level 1 → 2 → 3** as skin adjusts. **5 nights/week for a 12-week course**, max once per 24 h. Jump to [§5 Quick Start](#5-quick-start--everything-you-need-to-know-to-treat-tonight).\n\n---\n\n## 1. Positive ID — what you actually have\n\n| Question | Answer | Source |\n|---|---|---|\n| Marketing name | **Tria SmoothBeauty™ Laser** | ✅ your QSG/IFU cover |\n| Same device as… | **Tria Age-Defying Laser** & **Tria FRX (Fractional Skin Rejuvenating Laser)** — renamed, same hardware | ✅ Tria's own `/products/smoothbeauty-laser` page now serves the **FRX**; resellers list \"Age Defying / Smooth Beauty\" as one item |\n| Internal model | **SRL** | ✅ IFU Technical Specs (p.31) |\n| Manual edition | Bilingual **English + French (Canada/intl)**, ©2019 Tria Beauty | ✅ QSG/IFU |\n| Regulatory | ✅ **FDA-cleared Oct 30, 2013**; repo cites 510(k) **K130459**; \"entire face, all skin tones\" | ✅ Tria PR + repo |\n| Laser safety class | **Class 1**, per **IEC 60825-1:2014** — invisible, eye-safe under normal use (still never aim at the eye) | ✅ IFU |\n\n> **Naming note for the repo:** files [03](03_device_landscape.md), [08](08_clear_brilliant_quantified_gap.md) and the [README](README.md) call this \"Tria FRX / Age-Defying.\" **SmoothBeauty is the same unit** — wherever those files say FRX/Age-Defying, they describe *your* device.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Verified spec sheet (from the IFU — primary source ✅)\n\n| Spec | Value | Confidence |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Laser type** | Diode laser, **non-ablative fractional** | ✅ IFU |\n| **Wavelength** | **1440 nm** (targets water → dermal collagen; same family as Clear+Brilliant Original) | ✅ IFU |\n| **Output energy** | **5–12 mJ/pulse** | ✅ IFU |\n| **Laser class** | Class 1 (IEC 60825-1:2014), invisible beam | ✅ IFU |\n| **Model** | SRL | ✅ IFU |\n| **Treatment levels** | 3: **Training L1 / Treatment L2 / Treatment L3** | ✅ IFU/QSG |\n| **Dwell per zone** | **L1 = 30 s · L2 = 60 s · L3 = 150 s (2½ min)** per zone, ×4 zones | ✅ QSG |\n| **Full-face session time** | **L1 ≈ 2 min · L2 ≈ 4 min · L3 ≈ 10 min** | ✅ derived from dwell ×4 |\n| **Cadence (labeled)** | 5 nights/week, **12-week course**; **max once / 24 h**; \"do not use longer than a 12-week course\" | ✅ IFU |\n| **Charger** | In: 100–240 V, 50/60 Hz, 0.15 A · Out: **5 V DC, 1.0 A** (or USB); charge ≤ 2.5 h | ✅ IFU |\n| **Battery** | Internal lithium (recycle per local e-waste rules) | ✅ IFU |\n| **Operating env.** | 5–30 °C, 15–95% RH non-condensing | ✅ IFU |\n| **Design life** | 3+ years; no user-serviceable parts | ✅ IFU |\n| **Warranty** | 1 year, original purchaser, US/Canada/UK only, non-transferable | ✅ IFU |\n\n**Per-level energy mapping (⚠️ from reviews/15MinuteBeauty, consistent with the 5–12 mJ IFU range):** L1 ≈ **5 mJ**, L2 ≈ **10 mJ**, L3 ≈ **12 mJ**. Note the level raises **both** per-pulse energy **and** dwell time — so going up a level increases intensity *and* MTZ density together.\n\n---\n\n## 3. The \"coverage, density & energy\" you asked for\n\nThe IFU publishes energy and timing but — like every home device — **not** coverage % or MTZ density. Those are reconstructed in [08 §3b](08_clear_brilliant_quantified_gap.md); here's the device-specific summary, now anchored to *your* IFU dwell times.\n\n| Parameter | This device | How we know |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Per-pulse energy** | **5–12 mJ** | ✅ IFU |\n| **Microbeam / MTZ diameter** | ~100–150 µm | 🔍 NAFL class ([08 §4b](08_clear_brilliant_quantified_gap.md)) |\n| **Depth** | **~300–450 µm** | 🔍 *wavelength-set* by 1440 nm — same as C+B Original; **not** a Tria advantage |\n| **Per-column fluence** | ~64–150 J/cm² (5–12 mJ into ~100 µm) | 🔍 high, even ≥ C+B — intensity isn't the gap |\n| **Per-session MTZ density** | **~30–180 MTZ/cm²** (L3/12 mJ ≈ low end ~38; L1/5 mJ ≈ higher count, lower energy) | 🔍 [08 §3b]; web anchor: home units \"do not exceed ~40 MTZ/cm²\" |\n| **Per-session coverage** | **~0.3–1.5%** of skin surface | 🔍 [08 §3b]; Tria patent discloses a 0.25–5% *design* envelope ⚠️ |\n| **vs Clear+Brilliant (high)** | C+B ≈ **650–1,270 MTZ/cm², 10%** → this device is **~10–30× lower density** | ✅/🔍 [08](08_clear_brilliant_quantified_gap.md) |\n\n**How the levels move density:** the level controls **dwell time per zone** (30 → 60 → 150 s). More dwell = more glides = more pulses laid into the same skin = **more cumulative MTZs**. That's the IFU's own qualitative claim (\"as you go up in levels… the laser will create more MTZs\"), quantified: **Level 3 ≈ 5× the per-zone treatment time of Level 1.** So \"increase your level\" literally means \"increase your density\" — the lever that matters most ([08 §3](08_clear_brilliant_quantified_gap.md)).\n\n**Bottom line:** energy and depth are genuinely C+B-class; **what's small is density per session** — which is *by design* so daily unsupervised use stays safe. The way you recover ground is **frequency over months**, not power (see [11](11_subscriber_qa_lowdensity_rejuvenation.md) and [08 §3c](08_clear_brilliant_quantified_gap.md)).\n\n---\n\n## 4. What it's actually *for* (read this before you set expectations)\n\nThere are **three different claim levels** floating around this device — keep them straight:\n\n| Claim layer | What it says | Status |\n|---|---|---|\n| **IFU cleared indication** (the legal one) | **Periorbital wrinkles (\"crow's feet\")** only | ✅ narrow |\n| **Treatment protocol** | Treat the **full face** in 4 zones | ✅ that's the labeled usage |\n| **Marketing** | \"Multiple signs of facial aging, entire face, all skin tones; 76% wrinkle improvement, 95% smoother\" ⚠️ | ⚠️ vendor study |\n\nAnd the IFU is blunt about what it will **not** do — it lists these as \"do not use, may not be effective\":\n\n- ❌ **Dyschromia / brown spots** (\"may not be effective… you may want to see your doctor\")\n- ❌ **Freckles**\n- ❌ **Veins**\n- ❌ **Pimples / active acne**\n\n**For your goals** (pigment + collagen, per [README](README.md)):\n- **Collagen / fine lines / texture** → ✅ on-target. This is exactly what a 1440 nm fractional does. Realistic, evidence-backed *modest* improvement with consistent use.\n- **Pigment / brightening / PIH** → ❌ off-target. Wrong wavelength (you want **1927 nm**, [09](09_1927nm_vs_1450nm_headtohead.md)), and the IFU explicitly disclaims pigment. Worse: in pigment-prone skin, fractional **density drives PIH** — and **27% of trial users had temporary skin darkening (5 of 60 lasting >3 months)**. So if your skin is reactive, this device can *cause* the exact problem you're trying to fix. Use conservatively and watch for darkening (§7).\n\n---\n\n## 5. Quick Start — everything you need to know to treat tonight\n\n### A. One-time setup\n1. **Charge fully** — seat it in the cradle; the battery light **flashes while charging and turns off when full** (≤2.5 h). May arrive charged. Cradle works on any 100–240 V outlet (travel plug adapter only).\n2. **Unlock** — if it won't power on, it's locked. **Hold the power button until you hear 4 beeps**, then release. (To lock later: hold power until the padlock icon lights.)\n3. **Patch test (first-timers)** — run it on your **outer forearm** at the level you intend to use; **wait 24 h**. If no blistering/scabbing (rare), proceed to the face.\n\n### B. Every-night routine (the 3-step loop)\n1. **PREP** — wash and **dry** your face. Remove **all** makeup, sunscreen, and product (they block the laser). Tria's Priming Cleanser is the marketed match; any thorough cleanse works.\n2. **TREAT** — see the zone method below.\n3. **FINISH** — apply a soothing serum/moisturizer (Tria's Finishing Serum is retinol + peptides; any gentle serum works). **In the morning: broad-spectrum SPF, every day — non-negotiable.**\n\n### C. How to treat — the 4-zone method\n1. Lift it off the cradle, press **power**, confirm it's **unlocked**.\n2. Press **power** to pick your level (it remembers your last). **Start at Training Level 1.**\n3. **Divide the face into 4 zones** (per the IFU diagram): **Zone 3 = forehead**, **Zone 1 = one cheek/mid-face**, **Zone 2 = other cheek**, **Zone 4 = chin/lower face**. Crow's-feet area is treated as part of the adjacent zone.\n4. Lay the **tip flat** on the skin and **glide slowly side-to-side**, covering the whole zone. The **contact light glows purple only when you're doing it right** (flat + moving + good contact) — and the laser only fires then. Forehead: you can also go up-and-down. **Keep moving — don't park on one spot.**\n5. **Treat each zone until it beeps**, then move on: it beeps **once** after Zone 1, **twice** after Zone 2, **three times** after Zone 3, then a **completion tone + auto shut-off** after Zone 4. Don't advance before the beep (causes under-treatment of that zone).\n\n### D. Hard \"do nots\" while treating\n- ❌ **Never on the eye, eyelid, or inside the eye socket.** Around the eyes, treat **only where you can feel bone under the skin.**\n- ❌ Never aim into your eyes (invisible beam; Class 1 but still).\n- ❌ Not over a zone **more than once per 24 h** (raises irritation risk).\n- ❌ Not on tattoos/permanent makeup, broken/infected/burned/sunburned skin.\n\n---\n\n## 6. The 12-week course & the level ramp\n\n| Week(s) | Level | Per-zone | Full-face | Goal |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| ~1 (adjust) | **Training L1** | 30 s | ~2 min | Let skin acclimate; confirm no bad reaction |\n| ~2–3 | **Treatment L2** | 60 s | ~4 min | Step up energy + density as tolerated |\n| ~4–12 | **Treatment L3** | 150 s | ~10 min | \"Best results\" level per IFU |\n\n- **Frequency:** **5 nights/week** (evenings, so overnight redness fades). ✅ IFU.\n- **Course length:** the IFU says **do not exceed a 12-week course.** ⚠️ Common practice is a break then a repeat/maintenance course, but that's beyond the labeled instruction — your call.\n- **Why ramp:** higher level = more energy *and* more density (§3). Move up only when the current level feels comfortable; if L3 stings too much, stay at L2 — consistency beats intensity for this device class ([11](11_subscriber_qa_lowdensity_rejuvenation.md)).\n- **Realistic timeline:** users report first changes ~2 weeks; \"best results\" several weeks after the 12-week course (collagen remodels over months). The honest size of the effect is **modest** — a real fraction of a Clear+Brilliant course, not equal to it ([08 §6](08_clear_brilliant_quantified_gap.md)).\n\n---\n\n## 7. What to expect & when to STOP\n\n**Normal, expected (from the 60-person trial, ✅ IFU):** redness (95%), stinging/prickling (92%), burning (83%), warmth (78%); also dry skin, mild swelling, flaking, and **temporary small brown dots** (the healing MTZ crusts — normal, flake off in days). Most resolves **overnight to ~3 days** and lessens with continued use. Treating at night is to hide this.\n\n**Watch closely / yellow flags:**\n- **Temporary skin darkening = post-inflammatory hyperpigmentation (PIH):** the healing inflammation makes melanocytes over-produce melanin, leaving treated areas *darker* than surrounding skin; it usually fades over weeks–months as skin turns over. (Distinct from the normal **\"small brown dots\"** = MTZ crusts/MENDs that slough off in days.) It affected **27% (16/60)** in the trial, and **5 of 60 lasted >3 months** → IFU says discontinue. Risk is higher in **Fitzpatrick III–VI / melasma-prone** skin, and **density drives PIH more than energy** ([Chan et al. 2010](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/21246574/); [08 §3c](08_clear_brilliant_quantified_gap.md)) — so **stay low-level + daily SPF**. **This is the key risk for your pigment goal** — the device can darken before it ever helps.\n\n**STOP and let it fully heal (or see a doctor) if:**\n- Skin darkening **persists >3 months** → IFU says **discontinue use.**\n- **Blistering, scabbing, crusting, raised/painful areas, or bleeding** — possible over-treatment or a more serious reaction.\n- Skin still **red/swollen from a prior session** — wait until it's gone before treating again (don't stack sessions <24 h).\n\n**Never use if:** under 18 · pregnant (untested) · on infected/cut/burned skin · over tattoos/permanent makeup · recovering from a peel/resurfacing/injectables/fillers · on body areas (only the face was tested).\n\n---\n\n## 8. Care, troubleshooting & the manuals\n\n**Care:** wipe the **laser tip with a lint-free cloth** if it looks dirty (debris blocks the beam and breaks contact-sensing); store dry, away from water; keep on the cradle between uses so it's always charged.\n\n**Quick troubleshooting (✅ IFU):**\n| Symptom | Likely cause → fix |\n|---|---|\n| Won't power on | Locked → hold power until 4 beeps to unlock |\n| Won't power off | You released too fast → hold power 1–2 s, release |\n| Purple contact light won't stay on | Not flat / not moving / poor contact, **or dirty tip** → glide slow & flat; clean tip; recharge |\n| Treatment sensation suddenly changed | Check level setting; clean tip |\n| Fault indicator (**!**) lit | Power off then on; if it stays, contact Tria Customer Care |\n| Won't charge in cradle | Reseat firmly; check cable both ends; try another outlet (battery light should flash) |\n\n**Tria Customer Care:** 877-321-8742 · customercare@triabeauty.com · triabeauty.com (per your manual).\n\n**Source documents (mirrored in this repo):**\n- [Quick Start Guide (PDF)](tria_smoothbeauty/source_docs/tria-smoothbeauty-quick-start-guide.pdf)\n- [Instructions for Use (PDF)](tria_smoothbeauty/source_docs/tria-smoothbeauty-instructions-for-use.pdf)\n\n---\n\n## 9. How this fits your bigger plan\n\n- **Keep it for the collagen/texture/fine-line half of your goal.** It's the most transparently FDA-cleared home NAFL (brand-held 510(k) vs MimiSilk's manufacturer-held K182498) and a legitimate **maintenance/cumulative** tool — just not a Clear+Brilliant replacement ([08 §8](08_clear_brilliant_quantified_gap.md)).\n- **Don't rely on it for pigment.** Wrong wavelength + explicitly disclaimed + PIH risk. For pigment, the evidence still favors **topicals + SPF**, and if you want a *device*, a verified **1927 nm** unit (clinic Perméa / a confirmed home Dora) — see [07 (parent)](../01_ipl_hair_removal/07_alternatives_and_strategy.md) and [09](09_1927nm_vs_1450nm_headtohead.md).\n- **Biggest lever you control:** **consistency** (5 nights/wk, full 12-week course) and **ramping the level** (= density). That's how a low-density home device claws back ground over months ([11](11_subscriber_qa_lowdensity_rejuvenation.md)).\n\n---\n\n### Sources\n- **Primary:** Tria SmoothBeauty™ Laser *Instructions for Use* & *Quick Start Guide* (©2019, model SRL; mirrored in [`tria_smoothbeauty/source_docs/`](tria_smoothbeauty/source_docs/)) — specs, indications, protocol, side-effect rates, technical specifications.\n- [Tria Beauty FDA clearance for the Age-Defying Laser (PR, Oct 30 2013)](https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/tria-beauty-receives-fda-clearance-for-its-age-defying-laser-229848541.html)\n- [Tria FRX / SmoothBeauty product page (trialaser.com)](https://www.trialaser.com/products/smoothbeauty-laser) · [Tria SmoothBeauty (trialaser.ca, Canada)](https://www.trialaser.ca/products/smoothbeauty-laser)\n- [15 Minute Beauty — Tria Age-Defying Laser review (1440 nm; 5/10/12 mJ per level)](https://www.15minutebeauty.com/tria-age-defying-laser-review.html)\n- Density/coverage modeling & the Clear+Brilliant comparison: [08 — The Quantified Gap](08_clear_brilliant_quantified_gap.md) (with its peer-reviewed source list).\n<\/content>\n<\/invoke>\n", "file": "13_tria_smoothbeauty_owners_guide.md"}];
function render(){
  for(const d of DOCS){
    const r=document.getElementById(d.id+'_r');
    let h=marked.parse(d.md);
    h=h.replace(/<table>/g,'<div class="tw"><table>').replace(/<\/table>/g,'</table></div>');
    r.innerHTML=h;
    document.getElementById(d.id+'_m').textContent=d.md;
  }
}
function show(id){
  document.querySelectorAll('.doc').forEach(e=>e.classList.remove('active'));
  document.querySelectorAll('.navbtn').forEach(e=>e.classList.remove('active'));
  const t=document.getElementById(id); if(t)t.classList.add('active');
  const b=document.querySelector('[data-t="'+id+'"]'); if(b)b.classList.add('active');
  window.scrollTo({top:0,behavior:'smooth'});
}
function setMode(id,mode){
  const r=document.getElementById(id+'_r'), m=document.getElementById(id+'_m');
  if(!r||!m)return;
  r.hidden=(mode!=='r'); m.hidden=(mode!=='m');
  document.querySelectorAll('.segbtn[data-for="'+id+'"]').forEach(x=>x.classList.toggle('active',x.dataset.mode===mode));
}
render();
document.querySelectorAll('.navbtn[data-t]').forEach(b=>b.onclick=()=>show(b.dataset.t));
document.querySelectorAll('.segbtn').forEach(b=>b.onclick=()=>setMode(b.dataset.for,b.dataset.mode));
const first=document.querySelector('.navbtn[data-t]'); if(first)show(first.dataset.t);
</script>
</body></html>